<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>U. S. Railroad Retirement Board -June 1996:  RRB Issuing Statements of Service </TITLE>
<META NAME="description" Content="Description of Certificate of Service Months and Compensation" (Form BA-6) which is issued annually to every railroad employee who received creditable railroad compensation in the previous calendar year.">
<META NAME="keywords" Content ="Railroad Retirement BA-6">
</HEAD>
<BODY background="smlmbosb.jpg">

<H1><IMG align=left src="EEGLE1~1.gif"><IMG align=right src="EEGLE1~1.gif"><BR></H1>

<CENTER>
<H3><I>U.S. Railroad Retirement Board</I><p></H2>
</CENTER>


<CENTER><H1><I> June 1996:  RRB Issuing Statements of Service </I></H1></CENTER>
<HR>
<H3><STRONG>

  Each year, the U.S. Railroad Retirement Board issues a "Certificate of Service
Months and Compensation" (Form BA-6) for every railroad employee who received
creditable railroad compensation in the previous calendar year.  These annual
statements provide employees with a record of their railroad retirement service 
and compensation credits in the preceding year, as well as their cumulative 
credits. 
<BR><BR>  Most employees will receive Form BA-6 directly from the Board by mail during 
the latter half of June, although some forms are distributed through employers.  
Employees who worked for a railroad in 1995, but have not received a Form BA-6 
by mid-July, or need a replacement, should contact the nearest <A href="field.html">Board field 
office.</A>
<BR><BR>  It is important that employees review their BA-6 form to see whether their 
own records of service months and creditable compensation agree with the figures 
shown on the form.  In checking the 1995 compensation total, employees should 
be aware that only annual earnings up to $61,200 were creditable for railroad 
retirement purposes in that year, and that $61,200 is the maximum amount shown 
on the form.  To assist employees in reviewing their service credits, the form 
also shows service credited on a month-by-month basis for 1994, 1993 and 1992, 
when the creditable compensation maximums were $60,600, $57,600 and $55,500, 
respectively.  In addition, the form identifies the rail employers reporting 
the employee's 1995 service and compensation.
<BR><BR>  Besides the months of service reported by rail employers, Form BA-6 shows 
the number of any additional service months deemed by the Board.  Deemed service
months may be credited under certain conditions for an employee who did not work 
in all 12 months of the year, but had earnings exceeding monthly prorations of 
the creditable tier II earnings maximum for the year.  However, the total of 
reported and deemed service months may never exceed 12 in a calendar year, and 
no service months, reported or deemed, can be credited after retirement, 
severance, resignation, discharge, or death.  In addition to regular compensation 
which generally yields service month credits, the form shows miscellaneous 
compensation, such as taxable sickness payments or some other payments to former 
employees which provide additional earnings credits but do not provide additional 
service month credits.
<BR><BR>  The BA-6 form also shows the cumulative amount of tier II railroad retirement 
payroll taxes paid by the employee over and above tier I social security 
equivalent payroll taxes.  The Board computes this amount in order to advise 
employees, after their retirement, of these payroll tax contributions for
Federal income tax purposes.
<BR><BR>  For former employees who received separation or severance payments, the form, 
in the section designated "Taxable Amount," shows the amount of any separation 
allowance or severance payments in the last four years that was subject to 
railroad retirement payroll taxes but did not provide additional tier II service 
credits.  This information is shown on the form because in these circumstances 
a lump sum, approximating part or all of the tier II taxes deducted from such 
payments made after 1984, may be payable by the Board upon retirement to 
employees with 10 years of service, or to survivors if the employee dies before 
retirement.  The amount of an allowance included in an employee's regular
compensation is shown under "Compensation Amount."
<BR><BR>  An employee who receives Form BA-6 with an incorrect name, address, date of 
birth or social security number can have the information corrected by contacting 
the nearest <A href="field.html">Board field office.</A>  If there is a name difference, an employee 
should be aware that the form may not show his or her full surname if the 
surname exceeds 10 letters, "Junior" or "Senior" was used with the surname, or 
the employee first worked for a railroad in 1995.  Employees may also contact 
a Board field office to request a detailed breakdown, by year, of all railroad 
service and compensation credited to them.  For most employees, the address 
and phone number of the Board office serving the employee's area is provided 
on the form.
<BR><BR>  Any other discrepancies in Form BA-6 should be reported promptly in writing 
to the: 
<BR>Chief of Compensation and Certification
<BR>Office of Programs
<BR>U.S. Railroad Retirement Board
<BR>844 North Rush Street
<BR>Chicago, Illinois 60611-2092.  
<BR><BR>The employee must include his or her social security number in the letter.  
The reverse side of the Form BA-6 explains what other documentation and 
information should be provided.  The law limits to four years the period 
during which corrections can be made.
           
                         


<H3>

<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE> Railroad Retirement Service
Credits and Pay for Time Lost
</TITLE><META NAME="description" Content=" Railroad Retirement Service Credits and Pay for Time Lost">
<META NAME="keywords" Content =" Railroad Retirement Service
Credits and Pay for Time Lost">
<!META SOURCE=paylst.txt>
</HEAD>

<BODY background="smlmbosb.jpg">

<H1><IMG align=left src="EEGLE1~1.gif"><IMG align=right src="EEGLE1~1.gif"><BR></H1>

<CENTER>
<H2><I>U.S. Railroad Retirement Board</I><p></H2>
</CENTER>

<CENTER><H1><I> Railroad Retirement Service
Credits and Pay for Time Lost</I></H1></CENTER>
<HR>
                                                   
<H2><STRONG>
The Railroad Retirement Board frequently receives questions from
railroad employers and employees and their legal advisors about the
Board's treatment for railroad retirement purposes of pay for time 
lost.  The most common type of pay for time lost arises out of personal
injury settlements.  Other types include dismissal allowances
and guaranteed wages; allowances paid for loss of earnings resulting
from the employee being placed in a position or occupation paying less
money; and reinstatement awards which include back pay.
<BR><BR>
It is important that agreements between employers and employees
involving pay for time lost are structured correctly for railroad
retirement purposes because they are often intended to provide an
employee with additional months of creditable service needed to
qualify for railroad retirement benefits.  The following questions and
answers describe the requirements for the railroad retirement crediting
of pay for time lost.
</STRONG></H2>
<BR>
<CENTER><H1><I>Questions Index</I></H1></CENTER>

<STRONG>

<HR>
<A NAME = "inside">
1. How do the railroad retirement laws treat<A href="#1"> "pay for time lost"?</A>

<HR>
2. What <A href="#2">factors should be taken into account </A>
to ensure that payment
for time lost will be creditable for railroad retirement purposes?
<HR>
3. What <A href="#3">other factors</A> should be considered to ensure that a payment
for time lost correctly provides the total of railroad retirement
service months intended?

<HR>
4. Is pay for time lost subject to railroad retirement <A href="#4">tier I and
tier II payroll taxes?</A>

<HR>
5. What effect would pay for time lost have on the payment of a
<A href="#5">railroad retirement annuity or unemployment or sickness benefits</A>
 for
the same days?
<HR>

<BR><P>

<H1><STRONG><I><A NAME ="1">
1. How do the railroad retirement laws treat "pay for time lost"?
</I></STRONG></H1>
<H2><STRONG>
Pay for time lost attributable to lost earnings for an identifiable
period of absence from active service is treated as compensation
creditable under the Railroad Retirement and Unemployment Insurance
Acts.  Since the intent of an award for pay for time lost is to treat
the employee as if he or she had actually performed compensated
service during that period of time, the effect upon railroad retirement
eligibility and benefits is identical to the effect of regular
earnings for which service and compensation credit is received.
</H2></STRONG>
<H4><img border=0 src="bloostar.gif" alt="*"><A href="#inside"><I>Return to Index</A></I></H4>
<HR><P><BR>

<H1><STRONG><I><A NAME ="2">
2. What factors should be taken into account to ensure that payment
for time lost will be creditable for railroad retirement purposes?
</I></STRONG></H1>
<H2><STRONG>
A payment must be made with respect to an identifiable period of time.
The months of the period of absence from active service must be
specified, for example "the 12 month period beginning September 1994 
and ending August 1995."  In the case of a payment for personal 
injury, the entire amount is considered pay for time lost unless, at
the time of payment, the employer states that a particular amount of
the payment was for other reasons.  The compensation is considered
earned in, and therefore creditable to, the specified period.
<BR><BR>
An employment relationship must exist in the months to be credited
with pay for time lost.  Allocation toward future months is permissible
as long as an employment relation is retained for that period.  If
a settlement agreement requires that an employee resign to receive the
payment, the employment relation ceases upon resignation. Allocation
after the resignation date is not allowed because it cannot be considered
time lost as an employee.  With respect to pay for time lost
allocated into the future, service months and compensation are not
creditable until the time lost has actually elapsed.
<BR><BR>
The allocation must also relate to the actual period of absence from
service for which payment is made.  Pay for time lost due to personal
injury may not be allocated to service months missing from an employee's
record before the date of injury.  Similarly, the amount of the 
pay for time lost must relate to an employee's normal monthly pay.  A 
monthly allocation of at least ten times the employee's daily pay rate 
in effect on the date of injury is ordinarily considered a reasonable
relationship to actual lost wages.  A lesser amount would be considered
a token payment and would not be acceptable.
</STRONG></H2>
<H4><img border=0 src="bloostar.gif" alt="*"><A href="#inside"><I>Return to Index</A></I></H4>
<HR><BR><P>

<H1><STRONG><I><A NAME ="3">
3. What other factors should be considered to ensure that a payment
for time lost correctly provides the total of railroad retirement
service months intended?
</I></STRONG></H1>
<H2><STRONG>
It is of primary importance to have a precise breakdown of an employee's
service prior to any allocation.  This will avoid allocating pay 
for time lost to a month or months already reported as service months.
Occasionally, an employee will have service months reported for
vacation pay, or by another railroad employer, for example, by reason
of paid union activity.  Credit can only be received once for any
given month.  Because the period specified is the period for which
service credit is due, a month allocated to the same month already on
record may result in a shortage of the total months desired.
<BR><BR>
In addition, deemed service months shown on Form BA-6, Certificate of
Service Months and Compensation, should not be considered in the
number of total service months when an allocation period is determined
if those deemed service months are within the allocation period.  A
pay for time lost allocation increasing service and compensation will
generally eliminate or reduce the number of deemed service months on
record for any affected year.  Deemed service months are the product
of a calculation and if the components of that calculation change as
the result of an adjustment to service and compensation due to a
payment for time lost, then the number of deemed service months to
which an employee is entitled is likely to change.
<BR><BR>
Also, the possibility that an employee has creditable military service
should be considered because such military service is not reflected on
Form BA-6 and may reduce the number of allocated months needed to
attain annuity eligibility.
</STRONG></H2>
<H4><img border=0 src="bloostar.gif" alt="*"><A href="#inside"><I>Return to Index</A></I></H4>
<HR><BR><BR>

<H1><STRONG><I><A NAME ="4">
4. Is pay for time lost subject to railroad retirement tier I and
tier II payroll taxes?
</I></STRONG></H1>
<H2><STRONG>
The Railroad Retirement Tax Act is administered by the Internal
Revenue Service, and only the IRS can provide definitive advice
concerning that Act.  However, it is the Board's understanding that 
the IRS considers pay for time lost as compensation subject to taxation
under the Railroad Retirement Tax Act at the tier I and tier II
tax rates and annual maximum earnings bases in effect when payment is
made.  Pay for time lost is not, however, creditable on the basis of
when the payment is made, but to the period for which the payment is
allocated.  Therefore, the taxable amount and creditable amount will
sometimes differ.  The employee's portion of the railroad retirement 
tax liability is usually withheld from the gross amount of the award.
</STRONG></H2>
<H4><img border=0 src="bloostar.gif" alt="*"><A href="#inside"><I>Return to Index</A></I></H4>
<HR><BR><BR>

<H1><STRONG><I><A NAME ="5">
5. What effect would pay for time lost have on the payment of a
railroad retirement annuity or unemployment or sickness benefits for
the same days?
</I></STRONG></H1>
<H2><STRONG>
Because pay for time lost is considered earned in the month allocated,
an employee is not entitled to an annuity under the Railroad Retirement
Act with respect to any months to which pay for time lost has
been allocated.  If an employee applies for retirement benefits at the
expiration of an allocation period, he or she should submit documentation
of the period covered by the agreement with the application.
<BR><BR>
Similarly, an employee is not entitled to unemployment or sickness
benefits under the Railroad Unemployment Insurance Act with respect to
any months to which pay for time lost has been allocated.  If a
payment for time lost is made which covers a period for which benefits
under the Railroad Unemployment Insurance Act were previously paid,
the benefits would be subject to recovery.
<BR><BR>
For more information on the treatment of pay for time lost for railroad
retirement purposes, contact the Railroad Retirement Board's 
Bureau of Research and Employment Accounts at 844 North Rush Street,
Chicago, Illinois 60611-2092.
</STRONG></H2>
<H4><img border=0 src="bloostar.gif" alt="*"><A href="#inside"><I>Return to Index</A></I></H4>

<H4><HR>

</STRONG></BODY></HTML>

HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Enterprise/2.01

</DOCHDR>
<TITLE>California Law Help</TITLE>
<html>
<body>
<h3>
CALIFORNIA LAW
</h3>
California Law, including the 29 subject area Codes, the Constitution and the Statutes, is updated as new laws are enacted.  These laws can be displayed or searched.
<p>
<b>To display the Table of Contents for a Code,</b>  select the Code and click on Search.   From within the Table of Contents, you may select a range of sections  to display by clicking on the underlined section numbers.
<p>
<b>To search by keyword(s),</b> select one Code, several Codes, or ALL for all Codes, enter the keyword(s) in the box provided, and click on Search.  Searching on multiple keywords will retrieve documents containing all of the entered keywords. 
<p>
When documents are returned after a search has completed, the order in which the documents appear on the screen is based on what is known as relevance ranking.  Each document is scored based on its relevance to a user's
question, where the most relevant document has the highest
score, or rank -- 1000 being the highest, 1 being the
lowest.  Documents are returned to the screen in order of the document with the highest score listed first and the document receiving the lowest score appearing last.  
<p>
A document receives a higher score if the words in
the question are in the headline, if the words appear many
times, or if phrases occur as they do in the question. A
document's score is derived using techniques such as word
weighting, term weighting, proximity relationships, and word
density. 

<p>
Each of the documents retrieved will be underlined and will consist of the name of the Code along with the range of sections corresponding to the groupings made in the Table of Contents.  The word(s) specified in the search will be found within these section code ranges and will be highlighted.  All code sections within the range will be displayed by clicking on the underlined code.
<p>
<b>To display code sections, click on the underlined title.</B>


<b>To display information about the California Constitution or California Statutes,</b> click on the underlined titles.     
<hr>

<h3>DETAILED TIPS ABOUT SEARCHING</h3>


<h4>Special Search Note</h4>
Words so common that they occur in almost every document are called
<a href="stopwords.html">stop words.</a>  These stop words cannot be used for
searching a document because they occur so frequently that 
they are not useful for distinguishing one document from another.
Stop words are <strong>ignored</strong> during a search.  If they are
inadvertently used for a search, the results may be undesirable.
<p>
<h4>Natural Language Search</h4>
The server can be queried using natural language questions.
The server does not understand the question, rather it takes
the words and phrases in the question and finds documents
that have those words and phrases in them. "Tell me about
portable computers." is an example of a natural language
question.  In this example, the WAIS server would search for
documents containing the words 'portable' and 'computers';
the other words, 'tell', 'me', and 'about', are called "stop
words" -- words so common that they occur in almost every
document and so they are not used for searching a document.
<p>
<h4>Literal Strings</h4>
A similar but more specific kind of query asks to find
documents that contain one or more exact phrases by
enclosing them in double quotation marks. This is known as a
literal. For example, the query<p>
<pre>  <strong>"search engine capabilities"</strong></pre><p>
returns only documents that contain this exact phrase.
The WAIS search engine performs a literal search exactly as
if you had used the boolean operator ADJ. Thus the above
example would yield the same results as<p>
<pre>  <strong>search ADJ engine ADJ capabilities</strong></pre><p>
For this reason, it is best to stick to noun phrases when
using literals; if your literal phrase includes stopwords,
the stopwords will be ignored.
<p>

<h4>Boolean Operators</h4>
The boolean operators, AND, OR, NOT, and ADJ aid in
establishing logical relationships between concepts
expressed in natural language. These operators are
especially useful in narrowing down the search.<p>
<strong>AND, &amp;&amp;</strong><p>
     The AND operator is helpful in restricting a search
     when a particular pair or larger group of terms is
     known. For instance, when searching for documents on
     the weather in Boston, a question such as "weather AND
     Boston" would return only those documents that contain
     both the word "weather" and the word "Boston". You can
     use more than one AND in a query, e.g.  "weather AND
     Boston AND November". Note that the C-like double
     ampersand (&amp;&amp;) may be used instead of spelling out the
     word AND.
<p>     
<strong>OR, ||</strong><p>
     The OR operator is often used to join two different
     phrases of a Boolean search. A question such as
     "hurricane OR tornado" would search for all documents
     containing either the word "hurricane", or the word
     "tornado", or both. You can also use more than one OR
     in a query.  A natural language question is much like
     having an implicit OR between the words, except that
     the search engine does more work in a natural language
     query to determine the relevance of words and their
     relationships in a phrase.  Note that the C-like double
     vertical bars (||) may be used instead of spelling out
     the word OR.
<p>     
<strong>NOT</strong><p>
    NOT is a binary operator. That is, it has to come
     between two or more words or parenthesized clauses. NOT
     is used to reject any documents that contain certain
     words. The question "basketball NOT college" would find
     all documents containing the word "basketball", that do
     not also contain the word "college".  Note, however,
     that this question would eliminate articles on any
     professional players that mention their alma maters; in
     other words, be careful not to limit your search too
     much with the NOT operator, make sure that you know
     what you're throwing away.
<p>     
Don't be afraid to use NOT!  One good search strategy is to
search for a broadly occurring term and get lots of
documents you don't want, and then to use NOT to filter out
the bad documents.  For example, if you're trying to cook
okra, you might search for "cooking AND okra" and find
nothing; but if you search for "cooking", you find lots of
articles on cooking meats and pastas.  You then can search
for "cooking NOT meat NOT pasta", and you might find more
interesting articles that eventually lead you to your goal.
Another handy trick is to use NOT to "break the 40 barrier".
Typical WAIS clients only display 40 documents, but if you
use NOT wisely, you can flush out the documents you don't
like in those 40 and progressively refine your search,
adding better and better documents to the 40 that you see.<p>
<strong>ADJ</strong><p>
    The adjacent operator, ADJ, is used to ensure that one
     word is followed by another in the returned document,
     with no other words in between. For example, "cordless
     ADJ telephone" returns only documents containing
     "cordless telephone" and ignores documents that only
     contain one of the words or that contain both but not
     adjacent to one another. ADJ will nonetheless work when
     stopwords interrupt two words; for example, the
     preceding example will find occurrences of "cordless
     for telephone". Note that the ADJ operator yields the
     same results as does a literal query. Also note that
     ADJ, unlike AND, OR, and NOT, is not a commutative
     property - "telephone ADJ cordless" does not work the
     same as "cordless ADJ telephone".
     
<p>
<h4>Mixing Natural Language, Literals, And Booleans</h4>
The ability to mix natural language, literals, and boolean
operators is unique to the WAISserver search engine.
Combining natural language and boolean operators enables end
users to better target their searches. For example, suppose
you were looking for documents specifically on portable
laptop computers that are not made by Tosuji Corporation.
The question could then be "Tell me about portable laptop
computers NOT Tosuji."
<p>
<h4>Fielded Search</h4>
For data sets whose documents have special data fields,
selected portions of the documents can be tagged by the WAIS
parser as fields. A client can then ask a WAIS server to
limit its search to those documents containing a user-
specified value of a particular field. This is called a
fielded search.<p>
The mail-or-rmail parse format is an example of a parse
format in which fields are tagged. For this parse format,
the WAIS parser detects the "to" and "cc" fields, the "from"
and "sender" fields, the "subject" field, and the "date"
field. An example of a question using natural language, a
boolean operator, and fielded search is: "company picnic AND
from=barbara". The WAIS server would then find email
messages about a company picnic that Barbara sent.
<p>
<h4>Date and Numeric Ranges</h4>
For a date or numeric field, a range may be specified using
the syntax<p>
<pre>  <strong>field-name    comparison-operator    value</strong></pre><p>
where comparison-operator may be one of &gt; (greater than),
&lt; (less than), &gt;= (greater than or equal to), &lt;= (less than
or equal to), or = (equal to).<p>
Currently, dates with the following formats are supported:<p>
<pre>             <strong> m-d-yy    m-d-yyyy    mm-dd-yy
              m/d/yy    mm/dd/yy    m.d.yy
              today     yesterday</strong></pre><p>
Only positive integers are supported for numeric fields.
If the comparison operator is =, then the range may be
specified using the word TO, as in<p>
<pre>           <strong>date = 4/15/93 TO 4/14/94</strong></pre><p>
Both ends of the range are inclusively specified.
<p>
<h4>Right Truncation (Wildcards)</h4>
A user can specify right truncation by ending a word with
the asterisk (*) wild card character.  This tells the search
engine to search on words whose first several characters
match the base characters before the *.  For example, you
might use right truncation in a question such as geo*, which
may retrieve documents containing the words: geographer,
geography, geologist, geometry, geometrical, etc.
<p>
<h4>Grouping Search Terms</h4>
A user can group search terms and phrases together using
parentheses.<p>
For example, if you wish to search for information about
snowstorms, tornadoes, or hurricanes in New York City, you
might search for "(snowstorms OR tornadoes OR hurricanes)
AND (New ADJ York ADJ City)." You can also nest your
parentheses; for example, "from = ( (ben ADJ wais) OR
(brewster ADJ think) )" searches for messages from either
ben@wais.com or brewster@think.com.  When you're using
several boolean operators, you should always group, to
disambiguate how the operators are to be applied.
<p>
<h4>Special Characters</h4>
The WAIS server was originally designed to be as general as
possible and, in this spirit, it ignores all characters in a
document that are not either an alphabetical letter or a
number.  In fact, non-alphanumeric characters usually
separate words for the parser, for example, "F.Y.I." parses
out to three words.  This rule also applies to queries used
to search a directory of servers.
<p>

</body>
</html>

<title>Indexing of Bills</title>
<center>
<h1>Indexing of Bills</h1>
<h2>Session 102 - (1977-1978)</h2>

<TITLE>State Constitution Help</TITLE>
<html>
<body>
<h3>
STATE CONSTITUTION 
</h3>
The California State Constitution can be displayed as a complete document or searched by keyword(s).
<br>
<br>
<b>To display the Table of Contents for the State Constitution,</b> click on the underlined title.  From within the Table of Contents, you may select sections to display by clicking on the underlined section numbers.
<br>
<br>
<b>To display the California Constitution,</b> click on the underlined title.
<br>
<br>
<b>To search the Constitution by keyword(s),</b> enter the keyword(s), and click on Search.  Searching on multiple keywords will retrieve documents containing all of the entered keywords.  When documents are returned after a search has completed, the order in which the documents appear on the screen is based on what is known as relevance ranking.  Each document is scored based on its relevance to a user's
question, where the most relevant document has the highest
score, or rank -- 1000 being the highest, 1 being the
lowest.  Documents are returned to the screen in order of the document with the highest score listed first and the document receiving the lowest score appearing last.  
<p>
A document receives a higher score if the words in
the question are in the headline, if the words appear many
times, or if phrases occur as they do in the question. A
document's score is derived using techniques such as word
weighting, term weighting, proximity relationships, and word
density. 
<p>



<hr>

<h3>DETAILED TIPS ABOUT SEARCHING</h3>


<h4>Special Search Note</h4>
Words so common that they occur in almost every document are called
<a href="stopwords.html">stop words.</a>  These stop words cannot be used for
searching a document because they occur so frequently that 
they are not useful for distinguishing one document from another.
Stop words are <strong>ignored</strong> during a search.  If they are
inadvertently used for a search, the results may be undesirable.
<p>
<h4>Natural Language Search</h4>
The server can be queried using natural language questions.
The server does not understand the question, rather it takes
the words and phrases in the question and finds documents
that have those words and phrases in them. "Tell me about
portable computers." is an example of a natural language
question.  In this example, the WAIS server would search for
documents containing the words 'portable' and 'computers';
the other words, 'tell', 'me', and 'about', are called "stop
words" -- words so common that they occur in almost every
document and so they are not used for searching a document.
<p>
<h4>Literal Strings</h4>
A similar but more specific kind of query asks to find
documents that contain one or more exact phrases by
enclosing them in double quotation marks. This is known as a
literal. For example, the query<p>
<pre>  <strong>"search engine capabilities"</strong></pre><p>
returns only documents that contain this exact phrase.
The WAIS search engine performs a literal search exactly as
if you had used the boolean operator ADJ. Thus the above
example would yield the same results as<p>
<pre>  <strong>search ADJ engine ADJ capabilities</strong></pre><p>
For this reason, it is best to stick to noun phrases when
using literals; if your literal phrase includes stopwords,
the stopwords will be ignored.
<p>

<h4>Boolean Operators</h4>
The boolean operators, AND, OR, NOT, and ADJ aid in
establishing logical relationships between concepts
expressed in natural language. These operators are
especially useful in narrowing down the search.<p>
<strong>AND, &amp;&amp;</strong><p>
     The AND operator is helpful in restricting a search
     when a particular pair or larger group of terms is
     known. For instance, when searching for documents on
     the weather in Boston, a question such as "weather AND
     Boston" would return only those documents that contain
     both the word "weather" and the word "Boston". You can
     use more than one AND in a query, e.g.  "weather AND
     Boston AND November". Note that the C-like double
     ampersand (&amp;&amp;) may be used instead of spelling out the
     word AND.
<p>     
<strong>OR, ||</strong><p>
  The OR operator is often used to join two different
     phrases of a Boolean search. A question such as
     "hurricane OR tornado" would search for all documents
     containing either the word "hurricane", or the word
     "tornado", or both. You can also use more than one OR
     in a query.  A natural language question is much like
     having an implicit OR between the words, except that
     the search engine does more work in a natural language
     query to determine the relevance of words and their
     relationships in a phrase.  Note that the C-like double
     vertical bars (||) may be used instead of spelling out
     the word OR.
<p>     
<strong>NOT</strong><p>
  NOT is a binary operator. That is, it has to come
     between two or more words or parenthesized clauses. NOT
     is used to reject any documents that contain certain
     words. The question "basketball NOT college" would find
     all documents containing the word "basketball", that do
     not also contain the word "college".  Note, however,
     that this question would eliminate articles on any
     professional players that mention their alma maters; in
     other words, be careful not to limit your search too
     much with the NOT operator, make sure that you know
     what you're throwing away.
<p>     
Don't be afraid to use NOT!  One good search strategy is to
search for a broadly occurring term and get lots of
documents you don't want, and then to use NOT to filter out
the bad documents.  For example, if you're trying to cook
okra, you might search for "cooking AND okra" and find
nothing; but if you search for "cooking", you find lots of
articles on cooking meats and pastas.  You then can search
for "cooking NOT meat NOT pasta", and you might find more
interesting articles that eventually lead you to your goal.
Another handy trick is to use NOT to "break the 40 barrier".
Typical WAIS clients only display 40 documents, but if you
use NOT wisely, you can flush out the documents you don't
like in those 40 and progressively refine your search,
adding better and better documents to the 40 that you see.<p>
<strong>ADJ</strong><p>
The adjacent operator, ADJ, is used to ensure that one
     word is followed by another in the returned document,
     with no other words in between. For example, "cordless
     ADJ telephone" returns only documents containing
     "cordless telephone" and ignores documents that only
     contain one of the words or that contain both but not
     adjacent to one another. ADJ will nonetheless work when
     stopwords interrupt two words; for example, the
     preceding example will find occurrences of "cordless
     for telephone". Note that the ADJ operator yields the
     same results as does a literal query. Also note that
     ADJ, unlike AND, OR, and NOT, is not a commutative
     property - "telephone ADJ cordless" does not work the
     same as "cordless ADJ telephone".
     
<p>
<h4>Mixing Natural Language, Literals, And Booleans</h4>
The ability to mix natural language, literals, and boolean
operators is unique to the WAISserver search engine.
Combining natural language and boolean operators enables end
users to better target their searches. For example, suppose
you were looking for documents specifically on portable
laptop computers that are not made by Tosuji Corporation.
The question could then be "Tell me about portable laptop
computers NOT Tosuji."
<p>
<h4>Fielded Search</h4>
For data sets whose documents have special data fields,
selected portions of the documents can be tagged by the WAIS
parser as fields. A client can then ask a WAIS server to
limit its search to those documents containing a user-
specified value of a particular field. This is called a
fielded search.<p>
The mail-or-rmail parse format is an example of a parse
format in which fields are tagged. For this parse format,
the WAIS parser detects the "to" and "cc" fields, the "from"
and "sender" fields, the "subject" field, and the "date"
field. An example of a question using natural language, a
boolean operator, and fielded search is: "company picnic AND
from=barbara". The WAIS server would then find email
messages about a company picnic that Barbara sent.
<p>
<h4>Date and Numeric Ranges</h4>
For a date or numeric field, a range may be specified using
the syntax<p>
<pre>  <strong>field-name    comparison-operator    value</strong></pre><p>
where comparison-operator may be one of &gt; (greater than),
&lt; (less than), &gt;= (greater than or equal to), &lt;= (less than
or equal to), or = (equal to).<p>
Currently, dates with the following formats are supported:<p>
<pre>             <strong> m-d-yy    m-d-yyyy    mm-dd-yy
              m/d/yy    mm/dd/yy    m.d.yy
              today     yesterday</strong></pre><p>
Only positive integers are supported for numeric fields.
If the comparison operator is =, then the range may be
specified using the word TO, as in<p>
<pre>           <strong>date = 4/15/93 TO 4/14/94</strong></pre><p>
Both ends of the range are inclusively specified.
<p>
<h4>Right Truncation (Wildcards)</h4>
A user can specify right truncation by ending a word with
the asterisk (*) wild card character.  This tells the search
engine to search on words whose first several characters
match the base characters before the *.  For example, you
might use right truncation in a question such as geo*, which
may retrieve documents containing the words: geographer,
geography, geologist, geometry, geometrical, etc.
<p>
<h4>Grouping Search Terms</h4>
A user can group search terms and phrases together using
parentheses.<p>
For example, if you wish to search for information about
snowstorms, tornadoes, or hurricanes in New York City, you
might search for "(snowstorms OR tornadoes OR hurricanes)
AND (New ADJ York ADJ City)." You can also nest your
parentheses; for example, "from = ( (ben ADJ wais) OR
(brewster ADJ think) )" searches for messages from either
ben@wais.com or brewster@think.com.  When you're using
several boolean operators, you should always group, to
disambiguate how the operators are to be applied.
<p>
<p>
<h4>Special Characters</h4>
The WAIS server was originally designed to be as general as
possible and, in this spirit, it ignores all characters in a
document that are not either an alphabetical letter or a
number.  In fact, non-alphanumeric characters usually
separate words for the parser, for example, "F.Y.I." parses
out to three words.  This rule also applies to queries used
to search a directory of servers.
<p>


</body>
</html>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO>WTX098-B06-167</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA092-000987-B036-378</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.leginfo.ca.gov:80/help/statuteh.html 192.234.213.1 19970110054852 text/html 11446
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Enterprise/2.01
Date: Fri, 10 Jan 1997 05:47:28 GMT
Accept-ranges: bytes
Last-modified: Wed, 02 Oct 1996 21:33:24 GMT
Content-length: 11240

</DOCHDR>
<TITLE>Statutes Help</TITLE>
<html>
<body>
<h3>
STATUTES
</h3>
Statutes, chaptered bills, are available starting from January, 1993.    
<br>
<br>
<b>If you know the chapter number and year,</b> enter the number and year in the boxes provided, and click on Search.
<br>
<br>
<b>If you do not know the chapter year,</b> enter the chapter number in the box  provided.  The system will retrieve all the chapters with that number beginning with 1993.  
<br>
<br>
<b>If you do not know the chapter number,</b> but know the bill number, go to the Bill Information page and request it by the Assembly or Senate bill number.  The final version of the Assembly or Senate  bill which has passed through both Houses and been signed by the Governor will contain the Chapter number.
<br>
<br>
<b>To search Statutes by keyword(s),</b> enter the keyword(s), and click on Search.  Searching on multiple keywords will retrieve documents containing all of the entered keywords.

When documents are returned after a search has completed, the order in which the documents appear on the screen is based on what is known as relevance ranking.  Each document is scored based on its relevance to a user's
question, where the most relevant document has the highest
score, or rank -- 1000 being the highest, 1 being the
lowest.  Documents are returned to the screen in order of the document with the highest score listed first and the document receiving the lowest score appearing last.  
<p>
A document receives a higher score if the words in
the question are in the headline, if the words appear many
times, or if phrases occur as they do in the question. A
document's score is derived using techniques such as word
weighting, term weighting, proximity relationships, and word
density. 


<hr>

<h3>DETAILED TIPS ABOUT SEARCHING</h3>


<h4>Special Search Note</h4>
Words so common that they occur in almost every document are called
<a href="stopwords.html">stop words.</a>  These stop words cannot be used for
searching a document because they occur so frequently that 
they are not useful for distinguishing one document from another.
Stop words are <strong>ignored</strong> during a search.  If they are
inadvertently used for a search, the results may be undesirable.
<p>
<h4>Natural Language Search</h4>
The server can be queried using natural language questions.
The server does not understand the question, rather it takes
the words and phrases in the question and finds documents
that have those words and phrases in them. "Tell me about
portable computers." is an example of a natural language
question.  In this example, the WAIS server would search for
documents containing the words 'portable' and 'computers';
the other words, 'tell', 'me', and 'about', are called "stop
words" -- words so common that they occur in almost every
document and so they are not used for searching a document.
<p>
<h4>Literal Strings</h4>
A similar but more specific kind of query asks to find
documents that contain one or more exact phrases by
enclosing them in double quotation marks. This is known as a
literal. For example, the query<p>
<pre>  <strong>"search engine capabilities"</strong></pre><p>
returns only documents that contain this exact phrase.
The WAIS search engine performs a literal search exactly as
if you had used the boolean operator ADJ. Thus the above
example would yield the same results as<p>
<pre>  <strong>search ADJ engine ADJ capabilities</strong></pre><p>
For this reason, it is best to stick to noun phrases when
using literals; if your literal phrase includes stopwords,
the stopwords will be ignored.
<p>

<h4>Boolean Operators</h4>
The boolean operators, AND, OR, NOT, and ADJ aid in
establishing logical relationships between concepts
expressed in natural language. These operators are
especially useful in narrowing down the search.<p>
<strong>AND, &amp;&amp;</strong><p>
    The AND operator is helpful in restricting a search
     when a particular pair or larger group of terms is
     known. For instance, when searching for documents on
     the weather in Boston, a question such as "weather AND
     Boston" would return only those documents that contain
     both the word "weather" and the word "Boston". You can
     use more than one AND in a query, e.g.  "weather AND
     Boston AND November". Note that the C-like double
     ampersand (&amp;&amp;) may be used instead of spelling out the
     word AND.
<p>     
<strong>OR, ||</strong><p>
     The OR operator is often used to join two different
     phrases of a Boolean search. A question such as
     "hurricane OR tornado" would search for all documents
     containing either the word "hurricane", or the word
     "tornado", or both. You can also use more than one OR
     in a query.  A natural language question is much like
     having an implicit OR between the words, except that
     the search engine does more work in a natural language
     query to determine the relevance of words and their
     relationships in a phrase.  Note that the C-like double
     vertical bars (||) may be used instead of spelling out
     the word OR.
<p>     
<strong>NOT</strong><p>
     NOT is a binary operator. That is, it has to come
     between two or more words or parenthesized clauses. NOT
     is used to reject any documents that contain certain
     words. The question "basketball NOT college" would find
     all documents containing the word "basketball", that do
     not also contain the word "college".  Note, however,
     that this question would eliminate articles on any
     professional players that mention their alma maters; in
     other words, be careful not to limit your search too
     much with the NOT operator, make sure that you know
     what you're throwing away.
<p>     
Don't be afraid to use NOT!  One good search strategy is to
search for a broadly occurring term and get lots of
documents you don't want, and then to use NOT to filter out
the bad documents.  For example, if you're trying to cook
okra, you might search for "cooking AND okra" and find
nothing; but if you search for "cooking", you find lots of
articles on cooking meats and pastas.  You then can search
for "cooking NOT meat NOT pasta", and you might find more
interesting articles that eventually lead you to your goal.
Another handy trick is to use NOT to "break the 40 barrier".
Typical WAIS clients only display 40 documents, but if you
use NOT wisely, you can flush out the documents you don't
like in those 40 and progressively refine your search,
adding better and better documents to the 40 that you see.<p>
<strong>ADJ</strong><p>
     The adjacent operator, ADJ, is used to ensure that one
     word is followed by another in the returned document,
     with no other words in between. For example, "cordless
     ADJ telephone" returns only documents containing
     "cordless telephone" and ignores documents that only
     contain one of the words or that contain both but not
     adjacent to one another. ADJ will nonetheless work when
     stopwords interrupt two words; for example, the
     preceding example will find occurrences of "cordless
     for telephone". Note that the ADJ operator yields the
     same results as does a literal query. Also note that
     ADJ, unlike AND, OR, and NOT, is not a commutative
     property - "telephone ADJ cordless" does not work the
     same as "cordless ADJ telephone".
     
<p>
<h4>Mixing Natural Language, Literals, And Booleans</h4>
The ability to mix natural language, literals, and boolean
operators is unique to the WAISserver search engine.
Combining natural language and boolean operators enables end
users to better target their searches. For example, suppose
you were looking for documents specifically on portable
laptop computers that are not made by Tosuji Corporation.
The question could then be "Tell me about portable laptop
computers NOT Tosuji."
<p>
<h4>Fielded Search</h4>
For data sets whose documents have special data fields,
selected portions of the documents can be tagged by the WAIS
parser as fields. A client can then ask a WAIS server to
limit its search to those documents containing a user-
specified value of a particular field. This is called a
fielded search.<p>
The mail-or-rmail parse format is an example of a parse
format in which fields are tagged. For this parse format,
the WAIS parser detects the "to" and "cc" fields, the "from"
and "sender" fields, the "subject" field, and the "date"
field. An example of a question using natural language, a
boolean operator, and fielded search is: "company picnic AND
from=barbara". The WAIS server would then find email
messages about a company picnic that Barbara sent.
<p>
<h4>Date and Numeric Ranges</h4>
For a date or numeric field, a range may be specified using
the syntax<p>
<pre>  <strong>field-name    comparison-operator    value</strong></pre><p>
where comparison-operator may be one of &gt; (greater than),
&lt; (less than), &gt;= (greater than or equal to), &lt;= (less than
or equal to), or = (equal to).<p>
Currently, dates with the following formats are supported:<p>
<pre>             <strong> m-d-yy    m-d-yyyy    mm-dd-yy
              m/d/yy    mm/dd/yy    m.d.yy
              today     yesterday</strong></pre><p>
Only positive integers are supported for numeric fields.
If the comparison operator is =, then the range may be
specified using the word TO, as in<p>
<pre>           <strong>date = 4/15/93 TO 4/14/94</strong></pre><p>
Both ends of the range are inclusively specified.
<p>
<h4>Right Truncation (Wildcards)</h4>
A user can specify right truncation by ending a word with
the asterisk (*) wild card character.  This tells the search
engine to search on words whose first several characters
match the base characters before the *.  For example, you
might use right truncation in a question such as geo*, which
may retrieve documents containing the words: geographer,
geography, geologist, geometry, geometrical, etc.
<p>
<h4>Grouping Search Terms</h4>
A user can group search terms and phrases together using
parentheses.<p>
For example, if you wish to search for information about
snowstorms, tornadoes, or hurricanes in New York City, you
might search for "(snowstorms OR tornadoes OR hurricanes)
AND (New ADJ York ADJ City)." You can also nest your
parentheses; for example, "from = ( (ben ADJ wais) OR
(brewster ADJ think) )" searches for messages from either
ben@wais.com or brewster@think.com.  When you're using
several boolean operators, you should always group, to
disambiguate how the operators are to be applied.
<p>
<h4>Special Characters</h4>
The WAIS server was originally designed to be as general as
possible and, in this spirit, it ignores all characters in a
document that are not either an alphabetical letter or a
number.  In fact, non-alphanumeric characters usually
separate words for the parser, for example, "F.Y.I." parses
out to three words.  This rule also applies to queries used
to search a directory of servers.
<p>



</body>
</html>

<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>Spirit Venture Ministries by Leonard I. Sweet</TITLE>
</HEAD><BODY BGCOLOR="#68228B" TEXT="#FFDD00" LINK="#FFFF00" VLINK="#DD9900" ALINK="#FFFF00">

<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../sscafe.gif"><P>
<H2><I>"A Survival Guide For the Third Millennium"</I></H2>
<H2>August 1995</H2>
<H3><I>Volume 1, Number 5</I></H3>
</CENTER>

<HR SIZE=4 WIDTH=100% ALIGN=center NOSHADE><P>

<H1 ALIGN=center>The Real Made Visible</H1>

<CENTER><A HREF="v1n5.gif"><IMG SRC="v1n5s.gif" BORDER=6 VSPACE=15 HSPACE=15 ALT="Miniature Scan of an Issue of Sweet's SoulCafe"><BR>
<I>Click for larger image!</I></A></CENTER><P>

<H2 ALIGN=center>"Acupuncture by silver skewers of rain the earth
revivifies..."<BR>
poet Cecil Rajendra</H2>

God has such a weird sense of humor. For the past few years I have been quoting flippantly Peter Drucker's aphorism that the future belongs to three different kids of people: those who are crazy, crooked, and quick change artists. These past few months God has decided it was time for me to give the aphorism my personal due regarding, dues-paying acknowledgment.<P>

"Into everyone's life some rain must fall." How many sermons have I preached on what it means to live rain-lashed lives? How many times have I lectured in painstaking and (I confess) pain-inducing detail that every one of us will not get out of life without experiences of suffering, failure, disability, and death? How often have I argued that everyone of us needs personal "disasters" to make us, and to make us the person God intends us to be?<P>

<CENTER><B>
"The ultimate measure of a man is not where he stands in moments of
comfort and convenience, but where he stands at times of challenge and
controversy."<BR>
Martin Luther King, Jr.<P>
</B></CENTER>

My favourite illustration of this has been the Chevy Chase remake of the classic movie The Invisible Man. Chase becomes invisible after an industrial accident. Henceforth he could only be seen when outlined by rain, powdered concrete, or something that fell on him . It's the same way in life. You don't really know the values or value of a person until the rain falls, or a bag of powdered concrete falls on one's head.<P>

But the song says that "some rain must fall" in everyone's life. "Some rain" is different from tornadoes of quick change, hailstorms of crookedness and hurricanes of craziness, in that order. After eleven wonderful years at United Theological Seminary (UTS), my decision to accept the invitation to become dean of the Theological School at one of the church's great universities, Drew University (starting 1 September), brought with it a rush of the brain, a tug at the heart and a know in the stomach that hasn't gone away. The joy and excitement of this 'quick change" in my life was quickly mixed with the news of the bankruptcy of the "Christian" foundation New Era, in which UTS (along with 300+ other charities) had venture capital monies invested. This New Era shock to the moral nervous system-which proved Drucker prophetic about the persistence of that old era "sin," and made those of us in development realize how much snake oil is actually out there-added to the knot and the tug a feeling like vomiting but without the ability to actually bring anything up (there are some authors that leave me feeling this way as well-thy shall go nameless).<P>

My mother used to tell me and my brothers,"Boys, God never wastes an experience." It is still too early to tell what the experiences of these past two months will lead to.<P>

Already they have led me back to basics, to the meaning of an ensouled life to the rediscovery of the sheer joy of living and to engage in the spiritual exercise of assembling my own personal list of "These are a Few of My Favorite Things."<P>

The Russian poet Joseph Brodsky, who was a Nobel laureate in this 40's, ended his poem on his 40th birthday like this:<P>

<CENTER><B>
"Yet until brown clay has been crammed down my larynx, only gratitude
will be gushing from it."<BR>
Joseph Brodsky<P>
</B></CENTER>

The 21st century-with all its craziness, crookedness, and change-or-be-changedness-is already here. This new world is not for faint hearts, weak stomachs or stodgy minds. But whatever the future brings, "only gratitude will be gushing" from this soul. In the ageless words of Mabel Boggs Sweet, "God never wastes an experience."<P>

<DIV ALIGN=right>Leonard I. Sweet</DIV><P>

<HR SIZE=4 WIDTH=100% ALIGN=center NOSHADE><P>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Hazards With In-Line Roller Skates: Safety Alert</TITLE>

</HEAD>


<BODY  BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<center>

<a name="top"></a>


<a href= "/tango/ads/banner.qry?function=link">

<img src="/tango/ads/banner.qry?page=182&cat=4" height=60 width=468> </a> <hr>

<img src="/images/KIDSRCE.btn.gif" height=56 width=144 alt = "KidSource OnLine">

<H2>Safety Commission Warns About Hazards With Inline Roller Skates: Safety Alert

</H2>


<H3>CPSC Document #5050</H3>

</center><BR>


<HR size=3>

<table border=0 valign="top" halign="left" cellpadding="5">

<tr>

<td valign=top halign=left width=100>


<H3>Source</H3>

<a href="index.html">United States Consumer Product Safety Commission</a><BR><BR>

<hr width=75 align=left>


<H3>Forums</H3>

<a href="/Forums?14@@.ee6b2bb">Health, Safety, Nutrition and Kids</a><BR><BR>


<hr width=75 align=left>

<h3> Related Articles </h3>

<a href="/kidsource/content/toys_ply.html">The Toy Manufacturers of America Guide to Toys and Play 


</a><BR><BR>

<a href="/CPSC/Kids.helmets.html">Kids Speak Out on Bike Helmets


</a><BR><BR>


<hr width=75 align=left>

<BR>


</td>

<td valign=top>



<P>The U.S. Consumer Product Safety Commission (CPSC) warns that

inline roller skating--a popular new sport--can be hazardous if

skaters do not wear helmets and other protective equipment or do

not learn to skate and stop safely. As use of in-line roller

skates has increased, it appears that the number of injuries also

has increased.</P>


<P>CPSC recommends these safety tips to help prevent injuries with

inline roller skates:</P>

<p>

<ul>


<li> Wear a helmet, intended for use with skateboards or roller

skates, along with knee pads, elbow pads, and gloves. <br><br>


<li>Skate on smooth, paved surfaces without any traffic. Avoid

skating on streets, driveways, or surfaces with water, sand,

gravel, or dirt.<br><br>


<li> Learn to stop safely using the brake pads at the heel of most

inline roller skates. With one foot somewhat in front of the

other, raise the toes of the front foot and push, down on the

heel brake.

<br><br>

<li> Do not skate at night because of your difficulty in being seen

and your difficulty seeing obstacles or other skaters.


</ul>

</p>


</td>

</tr>

</table>

<html><head><title>Culver-Palms United Methodist Church</title></head><body><body bgcolor="#ffffff"text="#111111"><center><img src="meth1.gif" width=61 height=104 border=0><P><h3>Culver-Palms United Methodist Church<p></h3><h2>Soundings: short discussions of faith journey issues</h2><P></center> <h3><A NAME="menu">Soundings menu - click on your selection<p></a><h3><A HREF="#Christmas">Christmas Soundings<br></a><A HREF="#family">Being Family</a><br><A HREF="#money">Money</a><br><A HREF="#bottom">Return to the Home Page and/or send e-mail to Rev. Terry Van Hook with your comments, questions or requests.</a><P><h2><center><A NAME="Christmas"> Christmas Soundings<p></a></center></h2>
"ST. NICK" was a real person!    Known as St. Nicholas, this individual lived
in Asia Minor (present day Turkey) in the fourth century.
He was a Bishop of the early church and was assigned to the district of
Myrna.
He is said to have been an exceedingly generous many, going out of his way to
provide anonymous gifts to the poor.
Over the years he has become the patron saint of cities, countries and
especially children.  The Roman Catholic church set his "feast day" on
December 6 and began to exchange gifts in his honor.  Reformers in the 16th, 17th and 18th centuries (Puritans, Quakers, Baptists
and Presbyterians) were not happy with this non-biblical person and forbid
any celebration of the connected Christmas feast.
Into this vacuum rushed everyone else who had no such reservations:
merchants, party goers and of course children.
Father Christmas took over from St. Nick and Christmas was firmly established
as a secular holiday.  (The Dutch in New Amsterdam - now New York - held onto
their "Sinter Klass" which has been translated into English as  [you guessed
it] Santa Claus.)<p>

How have your Christmas traditions changed over the years?  Many of us
remember Christmas on the "farm," with wonderful smells of good cooking and
the ever amazing gathering of family, friends and neighbors.
Others remember special Christmas celebrations during wartime, illness or
little income.
It seems the ones we forget are the ones where everything went just
perfectly, we "got" what we wanted, there was not tragedy, no disasters.
The first holiday season I spent after my parents died was one of numbness.
 I sat in the midst of a great family gathering, watching games being played,
stories being swapped and a table groaning with food.
I didn't say much, but from time to time someone would casually wander over
and inquire as to how I was doing.  I'd nod my head and mumble something
appropriate, they'd smile and perhaps sit awhile, silently, by my side.
Then, after a while, they would wander off again.<p>

It wasn't until years later that I realized they each were taking a turn just
to sit near me.  Willing to take the time to attend to what ever needs I
might have.  <p>

The presents given that year are long forgotten, but the acts of love and
caring will last forever.
I and my family hope and pray that your Christmas season is filled with such
actions, old and new.  And with whatever gifts are exchanged, look deeply
into each others eyes and say "I love you!" (even before the gifts are
opened!)  ...and in so doing, make this Christmas one to remember.<p>

"It's in giving of ourselves that we receive, and in dying that we are born
to eternal life." (Prayer of St. Francis<p>

How's your life been?  How goes it with your soul?<p>

<hr><P><A HREF="#menu">Return to the menu.</A><P><hr><menu><center><A 

NAME="family">Being Family</a></center></h2><p> 


"Being family" is hard work.  Many of us learn that again as we work to pull
off the "perfect Thanksgiving" or the Christmas "like we used to have."
Today the stresses and strains of economic uncertainty, job loss and rising
costs play havoc on the best laid plans for a joyous, gift-filled Christmas.
The evils of family abuse, drugs, addictions and even crime have devastated
all too many families.  The struggles of getting the children to holiday
celebrations of now separated and divorced parents cannot help but dim the
excitement of the season.
It is a time when all too many of us feel overwhelmed by the world.  We long
for a simpler time, one filled with less problems and more joy.<p>

As we gaze over the long term sweep of history, however, we find things we
never as rosy as we remember them.
The rise and fall of nations, the sweeps of economic trends, the
devastation's of war and disease, have all left their mark on our lives.
Even the last few decades have not been without the shocks of assignations,
economic upheaval and personal tragedy.
The miracle of all this is not that people cope with all these things, but
HOW they cope.  
It's clear that some strategies for living (get all you can while you can)
will leave us desolated and alone.
What is often not so clear is the power and new-ness of life that God
provides even in the most common of circumstances.<P>

Christmas is the season when we celebrate the presence of God in ALL parts of
our lives.  
It's not just for a few weeks in December, it's not until the toys break and
wear out.  Christmas celebrates a deeper truth that changes our whole
perspective.
When we consider the gift of Christ in our lives, as a real and alive
presence, then our focus on getting "presents" is forever changed.
When we celebrate Christmas, the focus becomes giving rather than getting,
reflecting the love of God rather than going into hock to make others happy.
Christmas becomes an extension of Thanksgiving, a time of gratitude not just
for a good life, but for the gift of the Lord.<p>

Times are tough...  but the spirit of Christmas can be found in a
hand-written note, a simple meal shared among friends, a phone call not only
to share Christmas greetings, but a Christmas prayer together as well.
Let's not be distracted by all the flashy ads and music.  Let's promise to
spend some time together, as the family of God, as brothers and sisters
together in Christ.
Let's reclaim a Christmas that future generations will say: "We want a
spiritual Christmas, just like we had in 1996!"<P>

How's your life been?  How goes it with your soul?<P>

<hr><p><A HREF="#menu">Return to the menu</a><P><hr><P>

<h2><center><A NAME="money">Money?</a></center></h2><p>

"Money....  don't say that word too loudly in church!"<P>

I've been told that the number one reason people stay away from church is
that the church "talks about money too much!"
I guess that means that people are asked to give more frequently than they
want to .<P>

If that's the case, then I too would say that I'm asked too often to give.
 And try as I might, I just can't get away from it.<p>

Someone once wrote this modern day parable: "They want my money for the
McDonald's hamburger I buy, they want my money for the clothes and movie
tickets I purchase.
Even when I sit at home and do nothing I get requests in the mail to pay for
the utilities I use and the magazines I subscribe to.
There's no where I can get away from money!<p>

Perhaps if I saw money in a different light, as something that enables me to
be warm and comfortable at home, well read and entertained, clothed and
nourished with food, my attitude toward money would change.  Perhaps it's not
the money, but my focus that makes the difference." (end of parable)<P>

As we gather to be the body of Christ, as a close knit group of people who
seek not only change within ourselves but change in our world, we know it
will not happen without money.
Our church home has utilities and repair costs just as our personal house or
apartment has.  There are costs to the wonderful musical programs and regular
worship services.  
We want to provide the best Christian education we can for our children,
youth and each other.  We want to keep in touch through our newsletter,
mailings and other informational sources.
We want to have good and sound teaching from our leaders and we want to
recognize those who have given their lives and gifts to God by supporting
them as best we can.
We also want to be compassionate, helping those around us and around the
world who are less fortunate, coping with hunger, wars and natural disasters.<P>
 
We want an organization that is dedicated to spreading the good news of God's
forgiveness and love through Jesus Christ.<P>

In other words, we want our church to be like family, teaching ourselves and
welcoming new members, helping those in crisis and reaching out to persons
with deep needs. 
We what to challenge ourselves to think as God would have us think.  To
rethink our priorities and make sure we are going in God's direction.
And so we consecrate our "Estimates of our 1996 Giving", so that our church
leaders can prudently and wisely budget our funds in order that all these
hopes and dreams are realized.
We want to put our language of prayer, our quest for insight and our desire
to care into concrete actions, with real results and with accountable
responsibility.
So join us these two weeks of November, Nov. 12 and 19 as we talk about money
and as we celebrate it's gift of Holy warmth and Godly nourishment, Spiritual
Education and Missions Outreach.  
It's a word that should be said in church, even celebrated in church, for
what it allows all of us to do in the name of our Lord, Jesus Christ.<P>

How's your life been?  How goes it with your soul?<p>
<hr><p><A HREF="#index">
Return to the index.</a><p>

<h3>Culver-Palms United Methodist Church<p>
</h3>
<h2>Soundings: short discussions of faith journey issues</h2><P>
</center> 

<h3><A NAME="index">Soundings index - click on your selection<p></a><h3>
<A HREF="#faith">Will our children have faith?<br></a>
<A HREF="#violence">A response to violence.</a><br>
<A HREF="#easter">Why is Easter different from any other holidays?</a><br>
<A HREF="#bottom">Return to the Home Page and/or send e-mail to 
Rev. Terry Van Hook with your comments, questions or requests.</a><P>




<h2><center><A NAME="faith"> Will our children have faith?"<p></a></center></h2>

Will our children have faith?  Will we have faith?  Where will we
gain the
perspective to sort out and judge all the conflicting theories and
ideas that
surround us?<br>
Faith is that deep commitment to a guiding set of understandings
about our
world.  Faith is more than just knowledge, it is a trust in those
understandings that allows us to truly live.<br>
God calls us to trust in a way of living that is often at odds with
the
world.  <br>
Instead of the power and accumulation of things, material objects
and money,
we are called to put our highest value on each other.
Instead of counting our accomplishments and bemoaning our failures,
we are to
measure our love and caring.  
Instead of isolated wrestling with the inner prison of
self-centeredness, we
are called to look outward and see God's great creation.  We are
called to
open up our hearts and allow the love of Christ in.  We are called
to
honestly accept how much God loves us and allow the inner healing
that makes
all of us, no matter who we are or what handicaps we have, whole.
This is the life of faith.  One of promise and victory over the
world's
judgment of us.  One of deep peace and health even in the most
desperate of
circumstances.  It is a life that transcends the normal way we look
at
ourselves and challenges us to see ourselves as God sees us.

And such a Godly view does not stop there.  We are all called to
see others
in the same light.  We are asked to remove the scales from our eyes
and look
around us at people we may have known but perhaps never really
seen.<br>
We are asked by God to stand with the biblical heroes and leaders,
the
prophets and holy people and embrace them in the same kind of love
that God
has for us.<br>
This means not only working to put discrimination behind us, but
reaching out
in understanding to celebrate the differences that we all have.
Each person, whether they are rich or poor, middle-class or
upwardly mobile,
brings gifts and insights, stories and understandings that enrich
all the
rest of us.    <br>
God calls us to value people as the most important resource we
have.  And we
see each and every person living and breathing, eating and sleeping
in this
wonderful home we call Earth.<p>

"No one is an island"   John Donne reminds us and in this day of
ecological
awareness we become more aware of that than ever before.<br>
Let us be moved and shaken by our God who calls us to compassion,
insight and
love.<br>
Let us be loving as we explore and explain just how being a
Christian changes
us from the ways of the past into a new way for the future.<br>
Let us be bold as we invite others in loving ways to leave the
distractions
and dissipation's of their youth and adult living.  <br>
Let us look to a future that not only deals with the crime,
violence, hate,
prejudice and fear that the world offers, but overcomes it with
faith, hope
and love.<p>

These are not idle words, but the heartfelt motto of all who seek
to live in
Christ.  They are words that guide us and strengthen us.
They deepen our living and bring strength to our souls.
And they also reach out and beckon to others to find this live of
strength
and peace.  <p>

Think more about God as you go about your day by day activities. 
Bring up
the subject of faith and love as you speak with your co-workers and
friends.       <p>
 
Allow the presence of our Lord to become a growing presence  in
your life.        <br>
 And always be aware that you have something precious and valuable
to share
with those around you: faith, hope and love.<br>
Don't keep this good news to yourself.  Let others know what you
think about
God.  They'll thank you for life.  <p>
How's your life been?  How goes it with your soul?<p>
<hr><P>
<A HREF="#index">Return to the index.</A><P><hr>

<h2><center><A NAME="violence">A response to violence</a></center></h2><p> 

The issue of violence in our society is now on  the lips of
everyone.  As our
hearts are filled with sorrow, and we shake our heads in disbelief,
a crucial
discussion has begun over the causes and circumstances surrounding
this
tragedy.<br>
We hope that one day the perpetrators will speak clearly about
their personal
motives, and until then we must be content with a broader analysis
of the
trends and threads in society that encourage and promote such
behavior.   <br>
Listening carefully to what is being said, we must first recognize
that is a
complex and many faceted issue.  No one factor seems to be solely
to blame.     <br>
 Yet within our understanding there are certain aspects that seem
more
connected than others.<p>
First: the growth of the Survivalist-Militia movement with it's
rhetoric of
armed response to the threat they perceive in our government.  
There is a deep  danger in their "resistance at all costs" doctrine
that
believes the election process and democratic checks and balances
are no
longer working.  Theirs is an attitude that is often fascist in
structure and
has the same inherent evil that the KKK and other extreme vigilant
groups
speak of.<br>
While not all militia's are extreme one's they all feed off the
same paranoia
that not only is America not working very well, it isn't working at
all.         <p>

Secondly, we are in a rising storm of violence reflected in our
movies, TV
and Radio Talk shows.  Much is being debated about the power of
"talk" and
the freedom of speech.  It is critical to democracy to recognize
it's
centrality.     <br>
In this debate, however, we have lost the place of common decency
and respect
for each other when we differ.  Ratings and advertising revenues
have seduced
even the most careful "talk" host into labeling others as "wacko's"
and
"malcontents."   <br>
When we resort to such name calling, the only result is that we
create more
animosity and hatred rather than loving understanding.
I am not being naive when I say we have to reach a National
"ethical
standard" to turn down the volume.  We know that speech inflames
and leads
individuals to consider actions they would not normally take. 
(That's the
point of advertising, isn't it?)  So we must respect it's power and
use it
carefully.       <br>
Calling for the killing of the President or any Federal officer /
employee
must be roundly denounced and shunned by all.  Civility and care
for one
another must be the rule or else our democracy will die from this
cancer of
violence.      <p>

Finally, we must call ourselves not to an attitude of "my country
right or
wrong" but to the more honest "my country right and wrong."
We have a history filled with successes as well as some notable
failures.         <br>
 One of our crowning glories is the ability to uncover those
failures and
even endeavor to make amends.  The apology to the interred
Japanese-Americans
and the effort to redress the wrongs of slavery and bigotry are
shinning
stars in our nations crown. <br>
We as a society have much to be proud of, even as we address some
serious and
problematic problems before us.  We as a nation have charted new
seas in the
history of the world and it has not come easily.<p>

I hope and pray that each and every one of us can speak out against
organized
hatred, work to turn down the volume of the rhetoric, replace
violence with
understanding and take pride in our ability as a society to grow
more
sensitive and to learn.<br>
We may be only one voice in the wind, but think of the power if
others begin
to join us!                <br>
Pray for peace, be courageous in love, the darkness will not over
come us!                      <p>

How's your life been? <br> How goes it with your soul?<p>


<hr><p>
<A HREF="#index">Return to the Index</a><P>
<hr><P>




<h2><center><A NAME="easter">Why is Easter any different from any 
of the other holidays?</a></center></h2><p>

Candy and cute bunnies, clothes and Spring flowers are all becoming
the mark
of a more commercial Easter.  The culture is trying hard to
emphasize the
pastels and signs of hope as a way to mark the transition from
winter to
summer.<br>
Yet for Christians, people who have chosen the Christian lifestyle
as a
response to the fact that God has chosen us, Easter is
indispensable. <br>
All the other holidays: Valentine's Day, Halloween and even
Christmas could
disappear with only some minor adjustment to our Faith, but to lose
Easter
would be to lose the very heart of our faith.<br>
The Easter Story is more than new life and celebration.  The Easter
story is
one of great sadness as well as joy, filled with pain and struggle
as well as
victory and power.<br>
In fact, if we skip over the struggles Jesus faced, his betrayal
and his
death, we skip over the places where God stands by us most
powerfully.<br>
If we only take a few moments to celebrate all that is bright and
beautiful,
we lose the o opportunity for our painful and tragic places to be
comforted
and healed.    <br>
It is in fact that Jesus shared our pain, our lives, our hungers
and our
struggles that makes the victory over the grave all the more
powerful.          <br>
Here's a few ways to keep the eternal message of Easter before you.<p>

As you celebrate the holiday ("holy-day?") of Easter, take some
time to read
any of the Easter Stories of the bible: <br>
Matthew chapters 26 through 28<br>
Mark chapters 14 through 16      <br>
Luke chapters 22 through 24 or       <br>
John chapters 13 through 21.     <p>

These are the focal point of the New Testament.  We 
spend Easter
week reliving and renewing our memory of them.<p>


Come celebrate with us our Lord Jesus Christ who conquered the
grave!  Come
affirm the values of Love and creation that our God has given us. 
Come and
affirm that "nothing in all creation" can separate us from
Christ...  not
tragedy, not society, not government, not depression, not
distraction....<br>
 God has made an eternal promise in Christ that shall not die.
Thank God for EASTER!  Alleluia! AMEN! <p>

How's your life been?  How goes it with your soul?<p>
<hr><p>

<title> 
Weather
NPR Commentary

</title> 

</head>
<body>


<a name="top">	<!--REFERENCE POINT; TOP OF PAGE-->
<center>

			<!--HEADER GRAPHIC-->

<a href="../../images/headau.map">

<img src="../../images/headau.gif" ISMAP width=480 height=100 border=0 
alt="Atlantic Unbound"></a>


</center>


<p>


												<!--ARTICLE CATEGORY-->


												<!--DATE-->
<font size=+2><b><a href="http://www.npr.org/">NPR</a> Commentary</b>
 -- 
</font><i><b>December 18, 1995</i>
</b>


												<!--BYLINE-->


<br><font size=4><b>by <a href ="../../about/people/JFbio.htm">James Fallows</a></b></font>
	



			<!--SPACER-->
<p>
<pre>

</pre>

<center>

												<!--TITLE-->
	<h1>
	Weather Forecasting
	</h1>

												
	



<pre>


</pre>

</center>

												<!--TEXT-->

<blockquote>
	
													
	
	<font size=5>I</font> love my wife, so I am trying to save her from a
practice I find bizarre and dehumanizing. I am talking about a fascination with
weather coverage, especially those on the Weather Channel.<p>


Weather matters, of course, when it actually gets here. A sunny day is nice, a
tornado is bad. But the growth of "weatherism" -- the increasing devotion of
newsprint, airtime, and now a whole cable channel, to data about the weather --
is a social menace. <p>



Why? Let me find my list.<p>



Number one: Pointlessness. Tonight local weathermen will give their confident
five-day forecasts for the temp and precip ahead. They won't go back and tell
us what they were saying five days earlier about how things would turn out
today. I love going back to look, and what I've learned is that you'll do just
as well if you stick to this long-term forecast: for the next few months it
will be cold, especially in the north. After that it will get hot.<p>



Problem number two: Self-pity. Yes the wind makes cold days colder, and
humidity intensifies the heat. But today's inescapable "wind-chill" and
"humiture" figures are really just ways to impress ourselves with the hardships
we endure. Why stop there? Why not new weather formulas to tell us how it cold
we would feel outside if we had no pants on, or how hot it would feel in August
if we were zipped up, at high noon, in a sleeping bag?<p>



Number three: Lack of pity for others. There's enough weather in the world to
create a disaster someplace all the time. Typhoons, floods, sinkholes. For the
people involved these really are tragedies, but when we see a new one every
night they become video wallpaper, spectacles. Meanwhile people in the Sunbelt
follow the weather reports mainly so they can gloat at those stuck in Duluth.<p>



Problem four: Erosion of individual initiative. People turn on the TV to see if
it's begun to rain or snow. Unless you're locked up in a dungeon, there is a
simpler way to find this out.<p>



Number five: Damage to higher reasoning powers. Last week, on the anniversary
of Pearl Harbor, the Weather Channel ran a historical special on the role of
clouds in the attack. "Weather, which made it all possible," were the final
words. Each exposure to such thoughts takes 1 point off your IQ.<p>



Number six: Philosophical danger: Weather reports makes us fret and worry about
a future that  probably won't ever arrive in the form we foresee. This
distracts our attention from the time we do live in, the precious Now.<p>



And number seven: Unseemly hubris. Our weather presenters are happy when it's
sunny, apologetic when it's stormy, and in general act as if they are in some
way responsible for the weather they describe.  God or Mother Nature, take your
pick, is not amused. He or she will strike them down for pridefulness,  unless
I get there first.<p>

</blockquote>

<hr>

</ul>
