<p><font size=-1>Updated 27. October 96 at 20:36:20 GMT</font>
<H1>The long hair site / section "Hair care"</H1>

<P><IMG SRC="car001.jpg" ALT="[Girl relaxing]" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=214 HSPACE=10 ALIGN=left>
Hair care is usually annoying. When you comb your hair, you get stuck with knots. When you wash it, is doesn't feel good. It looks unhealthy. Just "bad hair days".<BR>
Take some time for your hair. Especially as it is long. Use some time during the weekend for your hair, and relax. Don't believe that wonderful hair can be achieved by any product within a few hours. It usually takes a couple of weeks before you really can see a difference.<BR>
It is important that you enjoy your hair care - men will certainly enjoy your look when your hair is fine!<BR>
This section provides you with some gathered information about how to care for long hair. It might be helpful for you ladies out there (or for you gentlemen, if you have long haired partners) to obtain nice hair. The base for all this is however that you have the type of hair that is suitable for to be long. Not every women can wear her hair very long - many women with short hair should really wear their hair long, but there are also many women who should get a hair cut soon, as they are really not the type for long hair.<BR clear=left>

/*
 * Flashy Eye-Catching Intro 
 * "Joaquin's Home Page,3,2,1" &copy; 1996 Joaquin T. Rodriguez
 */

function makeArray() {
this.length = makeArray.arguments.length;
        for (var i = 0; i < this.length; i++)
        this[i + 1] = makeArray.arguments[i];
}

function makeSlideShow (obj, wait, pre, url) {
this.curText = '';
this.posit = 1;   
this.word = obj;  
this.length = obj.length;
this.pre = pre;
this.wait = wait;
this.url = url;
this.display = displaySlideShow;
}

function displaySlideShow() {
        if (this.posit <= this.length) {
        this.curText = this.word[this.posit]
        outStringWord = blankFrameTop + this.pre + this.curText + blankFrameBottom;
        parent.draw.location = 'javascript:parent.outStringWord';
        this.posit++;
        }
        else top.location = this.url;
}

function displayLoop() { 
        if (wordIntro.posit <= wordIntro.length)
        reDraw = setTimeout('displayLoop()', wordIntro.wait);
wordIntro.display();
}

var words = new makeArray ('Now entering . . .', 'Joaquin\'s Home Page', '3', '2', '1');
var wordIntro = new makeSlideShow (words, 2500, '<CENTER><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><BR><FONT SIZE = 5>', 'home.shtml');
var blankFrameTop = '<HTML><BODY BGCOLOR = "#000000" TEXT = "#FFFFFF">';
var blankFrameBottom = '</BODY></HTML>';
var blankFrame = blankFrameTop + blankFrameBottom;

document.write ('<FRAMESET onLoad = "displayLoop()" ROWS = "100%, *"');
document.write ('FRAMEBORDER = NO BORDER = 0>');
document.write ('<FRAME SCROLLING = AUTO SRC = "javascript:parent.blankFrame"');
document.write ('NAME = "draw" MARGINWIDTH = 2 MARGINHEIGHT = 2>');
document.write ('</FRAMESET>');
//-->

</SCRIPT>

<TITLE>Dear Paula - Syndicated Newspaper Column</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#ffcccc   Vlink = "#FF0000"
Alink = "#FFFFFF">

<HR><P><IMG SRC="paula.gif" Align="left" ALT="Dear Paula (Gif)"> <Center><H1><B><I>Dear Paula</B></I></Center></H1>
<P><H4>
  	The following letters and answers are excerpts from Paula Begoun's syndicated newspaper column<I> Dear Paula</I> and from her <I>Cosmetics Counter Update</I> newsletter.<HR><HR>

 <P><H4>
Dear Paula,<BR>
I am 35 years old, and for as long as I can remember I have had old-looking hands. My mother says that as an infant, I had very dry, wrinkly hands. I now use sunscreen daily on my hands to help prevent further lines and wrinkles, but I am wondering if there is anything I can do to make the skin on my hands look smoother. What about AHAs? If so, what percentage should I use, and which products and how often? Should I follow that with hand lotion? I ordered a foot cream through the mail called Podiatrist's Secret Total Foot Recovery Cream. Would you recommend this for my hands?<BR>
Kelly, Yorba Linda, CA<P>

<I>Dear Kelly,<BR>
A dermatologist can do nothing for your hands beyond the things you are already considering. Now it is just a matter of experimenting until you find the right combination. The foot cream you bought could be an option, but I suspect it may be a tad bit too strong for hands and much better for callused feet. Hands rarely ever require the same thing as the feet. The "secret" in this product isn't really a secret. It contains urea, which, like AHAs, exfoliates the skin and also works as a water-binding agent, plus lactic acid, for additional exfoliation. You may want to consider an 8% AHA product in an emollient base to see if it creates a smoother appearance for your hands. You can try Alpha Hydrox Lotion or Cream 8% AHA, which can be found at the drugstore. However, you still need to use sunscreen on your hands to prevent any damage. Apply the sunscreen after you apply the AHA product. One more consideration: Be sure that any time your hands are in water or you are using cleaning products, you quickly reapply your moisturizer. Nothing is more essential than keeping the hands well lubricated all the time.</I><P>

Dear Paula,<BR>
Which ingredients indicate superfine glitter in a product? I have noticed a soft, fine amount of shine in some products and would love to know what's causing that.
I think you might find it interesting that my hair is dyed red through enzymes rather than peroxide, and I find this to be virtually nondamaging compared to using peroxide.
<BR>
Carolyn, Roselle, IL<P>

<I>Dear Carolyn,<BR>
In regard to ingredients that create shine, the culprit is usually mica or iron oxides, but the label won't tell you how superfine the texture of those components is. 
But what product could you possibly be using that dyes hair through enzymes instead of peroxide? As far as I know, and I am pretty knowledgeable about this kind of stuff, unless you are using henna or a semipermanent dye, both of which coat the hair and are not really "dyes," all products that change hair color from one shade to another (meaning you get grow-out instead of the color just fading away) use only peroxide and an alkaline base. In all my research, I have seen no other option. The product you are using may contain an "enzyme," but I assure you it contains the other stuff too or it wouldn't work. Even if an enzyme exists that is capable of removing hair color or opening up the hair follicle to let in new color, that very process is damaging to the hair. Perhaps there is something else about the product you are using or the way you are using it (such as not pulling the color through to the ends of the hair every time you use it) that is causing less damage.
</I><P>


<P>Dear Paula,<BR>
I saw an ad for some new products that were developed by an Italian physician named Dr. Romano Cali. He is supposed to be a renowned plastic surgeon who has created beauty patches that are supposed to deliver special benefits quickly into the skin. They are supposed to have healing powers from botanical extracts and other natural ingredients. The three products cost $99.95 plus $10.75 for shipping. Are they worth it? They seem a bit of a bother. Youre supposed to peel off the patch and then apply it to the skin for 30 to 45 minutes. What a bother. But if it helps, why not. 
<BR>
Alexis, Miami, FL
<P>

<I>Dear Alexis,<BR>
The Methodo Medique Complete is not only a bother, it is also an incredible waste of time and money. Healing power of botanicals? Helps combat the ravages of time? So extraordinary Methodo has received worldwide patents? I want to scream. In fact, sometimes I wish I could just let out a flurry of curses at these companies and the marketing people who write their ads. For $99.95 you receive precut pieces of gauze shaped to go over the cheek area, eyes, and lips. What magic formula are these gauze strips covered with? Nothing more than Vaseline. Thats right, Vaseline, plus wax, plant extracts (which can be skin irritants), and plant oil. This is a greasy mess, and each box contains only four treatments. I can practically assure everyone who orders this junk that they will be grossly shocked and disappointed. I dont know about you, but if this Dr. Cali exists, Id like to string him up by his stethoscope.
</I><P>
<P>
Dear Paula,<BR>
I am an educator for Nioxin research laboratories. I have experienced first-hand the difference this product has made in the density of my clients hair, reduced to normal levels of daily hair loss. The sheen, texture, and manageability [are] also improved. Perhaps if you were a licensed professional able to know the salon experience, you would be a viable resource tool. You seem to discount the fact that if consumers did not notice a difference in their hair after using a professional product, there would be no market for it. <BR>
First and foremost, Nioxin never, absolutely never, claims to grow hair. Nioxin believes prevention is better than a cure. Nioxin is the only manufacturer involved in the science of treating "living hair," that is, hair [in its liquid state], not yet formed in the follicle. Nioxin is cold mixed, having no sudsing agents or alcohol. The herbs and botanicals, amino acids and proteins, are active, [and] even considered viable. Just the cleanser (not shampoo) has the ability to dissolve (not strip) the buildup of resins and toxins, specifically "DHT"(dihydrotestosterone), from out of the hair follicle. Nioxin has no resins. The cleanser will normalize the sebaceous gland and reduce the amount of hair loss back to normal levels (between 10 to 50 hairs a day).<BR>
The reason I wrote to you in the first place was to let you know that finally in the beauty industry there is a product that stands alone. Nioxin is the only manufacturer with a 10-year track record in the thinning-hair category. Nioxin has set an unprecedented new standard of integrity, reliability, and education. If Nioxin was not effective, if the product did not live up to its claims, it would be alongside the road like so many others I could mention.
Nioxin is now worldwide, helping individuals cope with excessive hair loss. I am not saying that Nioxin is a miracle cure or an overnight quick fix. How many salon products have medical doctors referring them? Or wanting to have the product available in their office for resale? Have you experienced the devastating effects of chemo or radiation? The clients are often more concerned about their hair loss than the threat cancer poses. Let me encourage you to reconsider the possibility that Nioxin deserves to be left out of the negative connotations, and re-evaluated.<BR>
Sincerely, <BR>
Glynda via e-mail
<P>

<I>Dear Glynda ,<BR>
As a consumer reporter, I have stated repeatedly that if a product works for someone that is just fine. People can have many different reactions to all kinds of products. Consumer Reports alerts consumers to possible problems and concerns associated with a wide range of products; that doesn't mean all consumers will have those problems, but at least they can learn about the risks. It is a grave error to associate the popularity of a product with its performance. Cigarettes remain quite popular, but their ill side effects are well known. <BR>
Like any consumer reporter, I let people know exactly what they are buying and getting into. You should see the hundreds of letters I receive each month from people who say, I've been using such-and-such a product but it isn't doing anything, or my skin or hair is worse than it was when I started,?and they mention products in all price ranges. Unless someone exposes the other side of the coin, meaning the stuff the manufacturer doesn't tell you, how will consumers ever understand what they are really buying?<BR>
As I mentioned above, of course there is a market for products regardless of their effectiveness. Nioxin is hardly the only product claiming to grow hair. I have several such products on my desk right now that men and women have asked me to review. Are they telling the truth too? Do all hair-growing products work? As a reporter I can investigate and discover what the research indicates and what independent researchers have to say on the topic. It is my job to report what I find, regardless of whether my findings agree with the manufacturer or hair-care professionals.<BR>
I am not a licensed professional (although I was at one time, but thats another story altogether). I am a reporter who has interviewed some of the top hair-care researchers in the country, read most of the current published research literature and studies, and had long talks with the FDA regarding hair-growth claims. Perhaps you should check out the FDA's Web page regarding hair-growing products. All of these nonlicensed?professionals tell me that hair-growing products (other than Rogaine) and hair-growing vitamins do not produce the results claimed, and if they did, they would be drugs or over-the-counter medicines, like Rogaine, and regulated accordingly. The bottom line is I have seen no published or even unpublished studies heralding Nioxins success.
There is some benefit to keeping the scalp clean, healthy, and stimulated, and to following a healthy diet. All of these steps can improve hair quality, but Nioxin is not the only product that can do that.<BR>
There are great products in all price ranges. It is my job to help consumers find the best ones, whatever the price, although less expensive is preferred. I never discount what works, only misleading information and unsubstantiated claims. Speaking of misleading information, you state that hair grows in a liquid state. That is not the case. Hair grows from an accumulation of normal skin cells that are formed in the follicle and then pushed up and out of the root. Also, in a cosmetic, botanicals and herbs are rarely, if ever, active,?and there is no proof that they impact the hair or skin in any significant way, at least not in any independent studies I've seen (and believe me, I read them all). Additionally, there is no evidence that toxins of any kind build up in the hair follicle or that they would have an impact on hair growth if they did. On the other hand, thickening agents used in shampoos and conditioners, particularly those for African-American hair, absolutely can build up in the hair follicle and stunt growth. <BR>
One more problem with your comments: dihydrotestosterone (DHT) is not in any way a toxin. It is an active, necessary hormone that regulates the anagen or telogen cycle of hair growth. The process is very complicated, but how the hormone DHT binds to the DNA in the hair root is definitely significant for hair growth, both healthy and unhealthy. Cleansing agents and herbs cannot affect hormones, nor can they extract them from the hair follicle. Thank goodness they cant or we would all be in a lot of trouble, because healthy hair needs this hormone too.</I><P> 
<P>
Dear Paula,<BR>
I recently read some information about the "latest and greatest" in anti-aging and anti-wrinkling called pycnogenol (beta glucan). After reading about it in a magazine I searched on the Internet and found additional information and products to order. It sounds fantastic if it really does what has been said it can do.
Thats why I am writing to you, the expert in what works and what's hype in the world of cosmetic and facial products. The two products I found for sale were Martin Pycnogenol Ultra Moisturizing Gel by Martin Health Care Products (1-888-867-9673) and Pycnogenol distributed by Healthy Source (505-856-5004). The product seems to be formulated as both a capsule and a cream.
Can this product really do what it says it can do: is it anti-aging and anti-wrinkling? If so, does it take the place of all the AHA products on the market or can it be used in conjunction with an AHA product? I look forward to hearing from you before I place my first order for this new wonder gel. Thank you in advance for any information you may provide.
<BR>
Trisha, via e-mail
<P>

<I>Dear Trisha,<BR>
I am familiar with the studies regarding pycnogenol (a plant-derived substance), and I am not convinced. I don't think it is a bad ingredient, and it does seem to be a good antioxidant, but that is neither spectacular nor unique. There are thousands of antioxidants in the plant and animal worlds, and many are being used in cosmetics. Antioxidant is merely the buzzword of the moment in the cosmetics industry, which means everyone has to have their own super-duper antioxidant. Pycnogenol is just one of many. Products from Cellex-C, which uses a form of vitamin C (Avon is coming out with their version next month), to Estee Lauders Day Wear, which uses super oxide dismutase, are the reigning celebrities in the antioxidant world. <BR>
I have been looking into this topic from day one, and there is no evidence, and I mean none, that indicates antioxidants can change, prevent, or stop wrinkling. All the commotion is generated because the theory behind antioxidants and some lab work done in this area are compelling, which is why they sound so good, but translating what you can prove in a petri dish to human skin is a monumental leap. I have interviewed some of the top cosmetic chemists and dermatologists researching cosmetics, and all of them said the same thing about pycnogenol or beta glucan: It won't hurt your skin, but the hoopla around it is absurd and will be replaced by the next super-antioxidant to come along, and that still won't mean anything for the skin.<BR>
Even if antioxidants work, their effect isnt anything you would see overnight or even over months. They are still, in theory, a preventive measure. However, one area where antioxidants are proving to be helpful is in sunscreens, where they can boost the effectiveness of the blocking agents. Now, thats good news. But dont rush out and buy a sunscreen with antioxidants. That entire topic has a lot of controversy behind it. I have been researching the issue of sunscreens and antioxidants for the past month and will be reporting on what I learn in an upcoming issue of the newsletter.</I><P>
<P>
Dear Paula,<BR> 
I know you must get a lot of requests to review lines, but the Precis Skin-Care System seemed so intriguing I thought it might really be worth the money. I want to know what you think before I invest my money. I too am one of those women who take your advice seriously, because when I havent listened to your recommendations in the past Ive more often than not wasted my money. I know that puts a lot of pressure on you, but, well, that s why you do what you do, isn't it?<BR>
Judy, Birmingham, AL
<P>

<I>Dear Judy,<BR>
It isn't all that much pressure. I can only tell you what I discover through my research, but, as you know, the ultimate decision is yours. Always be skeptical of cosmetics lines that don't offer a sunscreen that s at least SPF 8, and preferably SPF 15, as part of their daily regime. If not, as is the case for Precis Dermalogics, all the claims about protection and preventing wrinkles are completely bogus. Here are my product evaluations for the Precis Dermalogics line of skin-care products, which is indeed serious but not all that sensible.<BR>
Refining Cleanser ($15 for 6 ounces) is a standard detergent-based cleanser that also contains clay and magnesium; all that can be drying for some skin types. It may be OK for someone with very oily skin, but keep it away from the eyes.<BR>
Skin Refresher ($15 for 6 ounces) contains mostly witch hazel, water, grape extract, pH balancer, water-binding agents, thickener, vitamins A and E, plant oils, and preservatives. Witch hazel can be a skin irritant for most skin types.<BR>
Rehydration Complex ($25 for 2 ounces) contains mostly water, aloe vera, silicone oil, plant oil, a long list of thickening agents, anti-irritant, vitamins A and E, water-binding agents, plant oil, and preservatives. It would be a good emollient moisturizer for someone with dry skin, but the most interesting ingredients are rather far down the ingredient list. This product also contains aluminum starch, which can be a skin irritant, as one of the thickening agents, but probably not enough to be a problem for most skin types.<BR>
Time Defense Complex ($25 for 1 ounce) contains mostly water, thickener, plant extract, aloe, thickeners, vitamin A, DNA, water-binding agents, RNA, plant oils, more thickeners, soothing agent, and preservatives. Although this product contains some intriguing ingredients, triethanolamine, which is considered a potent skin sensitizer, is high on the ingredient list. It also contains diazolidinyl urea; triethanolamine and diazolidinyl urea can be an unsafe combination of ingredients. As interesting as it sounds to have a product that contains genetic material, there is no evidence that it has any impact on the skin whatsoever. I'm afraid this product has more negatives than positives.<BR>
Conductive Hydragel and Neutralizing Cleanser ($48 for two 2-ounce bottles of each product) are two products packaged together. The Conductive Hydragel contains mostly glycerin, plant extract, water, silicone oil, more plant extract, water-binding agents, more silicone oil, vitamins A and E, plant oil, and preservatives. This much glycerin in a product can be an irritant for some skin types. The gel can actually feel warm when you first put it on. Glycerin is a good water-binding agent, but in larger percentages it can take water out of the skin. This could be a good lightweight moisturizer for women with normal to dry skin, but only if they don't have problems with the glycerin. <BR>
What makes the Conductive Hydragel somewhat bizarre is that it supposedly has a positive charge that works in tandem with a little machine called the Precis Dermalogics Activator ($79), which uses  "positive polarity to propel Conductive Hydragel's positive[ly] charged" ingredients into the skin. In other words, the Activator forces the moisturizer beneath the surface layer of the skin. Unbelievable. I no longer encounter many firsts in the world of cosmetics, but this is a first. There is no research to back up the claims that this machine can do what it says, but it seems unlikely that an electrical charge will help the skin the least little bit. Besides, how deep is deep? The skin is only so thick; beyond that youre getting to muscle and bone. Most moisturizers penetrate to the lower layers of skin anyway.<BR>
The Neutralizing Cleanser is nothing more than a detergent-based cleanser that would be gentler on the skin than the Refining Cleanser above. However, nothing about it makes it "neutralizing." Also, I'm concerned: why does the skin have to be neutralized?<P></I>
<P>
Dear Paula,<BR>
First, before I fling myself unashamedly at your feet to beg for your expert and much-anticipated advice, I want to thank you for saving me money, sparing me from disappointment, and opening my eyes to all of the ridiculous claims of the cosmetics industry. Before I bought your book Don't Go To The Cosmetics Counter Without Me (after reading that, I quickly went out and bought your other two), I thought of myself as someone who loved shopping for cosmetics but still made wise choices. What a laugh! Just what the cosmetics industry would want a consumer to think! How easily we're lured into making the most ludicrous purchases in the world while, with a self-satisfied smile, we slap down a credit card, confident we're making a wise investment in our skin-care future. <BR>
I very specifically remember scoffing at my mother's gullibility when she purchased the very expensive Creme de la Mer, while I, the more scrutinizing and discriminating consumer, purchased a $50 cream from Lauder a week later. I was supremely self-satisfied that I had spent $100 less than my mother and wasted no time didactically informing her that she needed to be wiser with her purchases. Since reading your books, however, I've completely stopped using moisturizer at all (I've got oily skin) and I could see the change almost immediately, it's clearer, not dull, and hardly ever breaks out anymore.<BR>
What your books do is provide consumers with evidence that cannot be ignored-telling us point blank, no two ways about it-that many products are simply incapable of doing what they claim. For many consumers out there (I was one of them), there is always that small amount of doubt (well, maybe . . .) simply because we don't know which ingredients are capable of doing what. I've already saved myself hundreds of dollars. My husband wants me to thank you too, because now he doesn't have to hear me ask him relentlessly after I've purchased new skin-care products, "Do you see a difference? Come on, dear, this will just take a minute. Does my skin have a bit more sheen than usual? Does the skin look thicker or thinner? Would you say that my skin is (a) glowing, (b) dewy, (c) translucent, or (d) shimmering?"<BR>
Now I'm wondering if you would be so kind as to review the Mariana Chicet skin-care products? I have several friends who just rave about them. Before I do anything, however, I want to see what you think. I understand they've been getting a lot of press lately. <BR>
Name withheld by request<P>

<I>Dear Reader,<BR>
What a great letter. You summed up perfectly why the cosmetics counters can be so seductive and misleading. I understand the intense pressure out there to get the best and the latest. For me, there has always been something very satisfying about sharing what I have learned about the insane world of cosmetics. Having interviewed and read the literature produced by so many inside sources who are leading researchers in the industry, I know just how really crazy it is out there. Your letter confirms that once a woman has all the facts, both pros and cons, she can stop throwing money at the cosmetics industry and still have beautiful skin. As for Mariana Chicet's line, it is reviewed elsewhere in this issue of Cosmetics Counter Update.
<P></I>
<P>
Dear Paula,<BR>
I usually do not take the time to write unless it is a complaint, but you are an exception. I want to thank you for two reasons. I started having problems with my hair about a year ago. It was acting very strangeparting on the wrong side, looking heavy, and feeling stiff. I spoke to several hairdressers and was told, "It's a cowlick," or "That's just the way your hair falls." I was very self-conscious and frustrated. Shortly after that I saw you on television talking about shampoos with conditioners that contain hairspray ingredients and what they can do to the hair. I changed my shampoo to one without conditioner, and the problem went away. That alone deserves a thank-you.<BR>
You also helped with my skin. I am 48 years old and have always had oily skin. I am Puerto Rican, and my skin color is sallow to olive. It has been impossible for me to find a foundation that works for me. Then I saw you on another talk show and you discussed foundations and which ones are the best and how to tell what the right color is. I can't tell you how much money I have spent on "makeup experts" who have sold me mauve correcting creams to put under my makeup to correct my skin color. You explained clearly the difference between oil-free and water-based foundations and [outlined] your inexpensive skin-care routine. I followed your advice and I can't tell you the difference. Who would have thought that my foundation would last most of the day! Thank you again.<BR>
Neida, Orlando, FL<P>

<I>Dear Neida,<BR>
Thank you for taking the time to share your successes with me. I am glad I could be of help. Letters like yours, which I'm pleased to say I get a lot of, make me love what I do.<P></I>
<P>
Dear Paula,<BR>
I'm wondering whether you would be shocked by the rather unorthodox method I've been following for the past few months to exfoliate my skin. I'd read somewhere of a theory that men have softer, clearer skin because they shave their face every day. Shaving exfoliates the skin and thereby leaves it softer and smoother. I decided to try it, so during my nightly soak in the tub I lather up with Pond's Cleanser and Toner in One and, well, shave my face. I've actually found it beneficial in removing peach-fuzz, and my foundation goes on much smoother and looks better than ever before. I especially like the effect on the skin around my upper lip: it really does seem smoother. I know this sounds crazy, but I'm very curious to hear what you think. <BR>
Name Withheld by Request<P>

<I>Dear Reader,<BR>
I have learned to stop being shocked concerning a woman's pursuit of better-looking skin, although I have to admit yours is a bit more radical than most. I've heard the rumor about men and shaving repeatedly over the years; I just never thought a woman would consider that method of exfoliation. Shaving absolutely exfoliates the skin, which can leave it feeling softer and looking smoother. Shaving can also help nick off the very top layer of blemishes or clogged pores, which opens them right up and helps undo the plug. Alpha hydroxy acids, salicylic acids, and Retin-A or Renova essentially do the same thing for the skin, but without hair removal and more evenly. After all, you don't shave your forehead and crows-feet, or do you? Of course, nothing about shaving (or any method of exfoliation) changes or prevents wrinkles. It just makes the skin feel smoother and helps reduce blemishes. Men, regardless of how much they shave, still have wrinkles; it is just more socially acceptable for men to have wrinkles than it is for women. The bottom line: As long as you are not experiencing stubble or irritation, shaving is not harmful, and as long as you find it beneficial there is no reason to stop. If you do experience stubble or irritation, stop shaving immediately. That is what men experience, and for them shaving is no picnic.</I><P>
<P>
Dear Paula,<BR>
I know you must be tired of always hearing about someone's cosmetic woes, but your books and newsletters have always helped me so much in the past that I thought you might be able to help with a problem I haven't seen you write about before. I have extremely sensitive skin on my body. I went to my doctor and she suggested I use Dove Unscented soap. I am still using it, but I continue to get rashes every time I take a shower. I'm not sure if it's the water or the soap I'm allergic to. I recently bought Dove Moisturizing Body Wash and tried it because I thought it would be less irritating than the soap, but I was wrong. I've tried so many products out there, even Cetaphil Lotion, but nothing seems to help. I would appreciate any suggestions you may have.<BR>
Marietta, Vancouver, BC<P>

<I>Dear Marietta,<BR>
If you are still experiencing this much irritation every time you shower, the Dove soap is not helping in the least and you should stop using it immediately. You said you talked to your doctor, but you didn't say whether the doctor is a dermatologist. For skin as sensitive as yours, a dermatologist would be able to prescribe a cortisone cream to help reduce the rashes and irritation. <BR>
I do have a few recommendations I'd like you to try after you stop using the soap. Please purchase some raw uncooked oatmealnot the quick-cooking type, but the kind you might find in a health-food store. Mix about a half cup of oatmeal with a teaspoon or two of water, and use that in the shower as a massage all over your body. Continue using the Dove soap under your arms and vaginally, but nowhere else, and be careful when you rinse to have the suds fall away from your body. When you shampoo your hair, also be certain to rinse so that the suds fall away from your body. I strongly suggest you try some over-the-counter cortisone cream (such as Lanacort or Cortaid) over areas that are particularly irritated. This should give you some relief until you book an appointment with a competent dermatologist. </I><P>
<P>
Dear Paula,<BR>
I am 23 years old and have a problem with blackheads. I have combination skin, and the blackheads are worst on my T-zone, especially on my nose. I've tried just about every scrub and facial mask on the market, in all price ranges, and nothing seems to work. It appears the only way to remove them is either to manually squeeze them out, which people tell me is bad for my skin, or to go for weekly facials, which I can't afford to do. I recently saw an advertisement in a magazine selling a device that removes blackheads by "soft suctioning," using a "vacuum-air" method of some kind, or at least that's what the ad implied. It supposedly entails no squeezing and will not puncture the skin. What are your thoughts on this? If this device is just a gimmick, what do you recommend?<BR>
Traci, Houston, TX<P>

<I>Dear Traci,<BR>
I have seen that same device advertised in magazines since I was a little girl. Like you, I was enticed by the promise; the difference is I bought it. What a huge disappointment. Not only didn't it work, it left small red marks on my face. I believe that was one of the first times I was angry at the beauty industry. I was all of 16 years old. What I learned back then was if devices like that worked, who would ever complain about blackheads? It doesn't work, but it stays on the market, advertised in miscellaneous magazines for other unsuspecting consumers. <BR>
The good news is that squeezing is absolutely a good option for removing blackheads, and exactly what you would be paying a facialist to do. You already have spent a lot of your hard-earned money searching for the perfect scrub and mask, which means you now know those don't work. In essence, the most important thing you can do to get rid of blackheads is to stay away from harsh products and consider a gentle skin-care routine, such as Moisturel Sensitive Skin Cleanser; an AHA product like mine, Elizabeth Arden's Alpha Ceramide, or M.D. Formulations Facial Lotion; 3% hydrogen peroxide over blemishes and blackheads; and a facial mask once a week of milk of magnesia (milk of magnesia absorbs oil better than any clay mask)<P></I>
<P>
Dear Paula,<BR>
I've read with interest your reviews of products that say they're oil-free but really contain hidden oils or other oily ingredients. My oily skin, which tends to break out, would love to know more about this. Could you list some of the chemical names and buzzwords cosmetics companies use in ingredient lists to disguise the fact that they put oils in their products. <BR>
Lorraine, Indian Harbor, GA<P>

<I>Dear Lorraine,<BR>
I wish it were an easy task to list the name of ingredients that can produce an oily feel on the skin, but that is more complicated a task than you know. Even silicone oils such as cyclomethicone or dimethicone can leave a matte texture on the skin, depending on the formulation, and have no effect on breakouts. What is perhaps most confusing is that even ingredients known for causing breakouts may not leave a greasy feel on the skin. Surprisingly, another one of the greasiest ingredients, mineral oil, has been shown in study after study not to cause breakouts. Go figure. <BR>
As a general rule, it is best to avoid any and all oils in skin-care products, including silicone oils, if they are high on the ingredient list. The only ingredients I would ever encourage a woman with oily skin to truly avoid are any ingredients ending in triglyceride, palmitate, or myristate, and ingredients such as jojoba (jojoba oil and wax can cause breakouts), lanolin, beeswax, candelilla wax, carnuba wax, cocoa butter, shea butter, and tallow (found mostly in soaps). Keep in mind that there are a host of ingredients that can aggravate oily skin and acne while actually feeling cool and drying on the skin, including alcohol, menthol, lemon, and mint<P></I>
<P>
Dear Paula,<BR>
I'm anxious to get your feedback regarding the Pure Science? products from a company called Life Extension. I'm including a catalog and ingredient information.<BR>
Bernadette, Corona, CA
<P>

<I>Dear Bernadette, <BR>
Maybe it's just that I'm an eternal skeptic, but it is hard for me to take any product line seriously when it is being sold along with vitamins called Natural Sex and Wow. Nevertheless, Pure Science? wants you to take them seriously. What sets this line apart is the inclusion of 24-karat gold flakes in each of the products. I have to admit these are the prettiest skin-care products I've ever seen. But given that you can't wear them as jewelry, what really counts is what they can do. <BR>
First of all, gold flakes provide no benefit for the skin. Of course, Pure Science? wants you to believe that the gold flakes can aid in "cell exfoliation, skin purification, and increase[d] circulation." That isn't supported by any evidence other than their claim. Gold can't be absorbed into the skin-no mineral can-and it can't leach anything into the skin. Gold's skin-care value is perceived rather than real. And be honest: wouldn't you rather wear gold in the form of a necklace or ring instead of in a skin-care product?<BR>
Despite my doubts about the gold, I found the information sheet about the other ingredients in these products, for the most part, refreshingly honest. It describes aloe vera as being 99.5% water with a trace of other ingredients. It also describes the thickening agents accurately, as well as the AHA ingredients. Somewhere along the way Pure Science? got sidetracked, because the other claims are just plain silly.<BR>
24 Karat Gold Intensive Moisturizer ($39.95 for 2 ounces) contains mostly water, aloe, thickeners, AHAs, plasticizer (hairspray), more thickeners, plant extract, slip agents, and preservatives. This is a good 6% to 7% AHA moisturizer for someone with normal to dry skin, but if you ignore the gold (and you should) it isn't any more impressive than Pond's Age Defying Cream or Alpha Hydrox Lotion or Cream.<BR>
24 Karat Gold Eye Lift Gel ($39.95 for 1 ounce) contains mostly water, glycerin, water-binding agents, soothing agent, more water-binding agents, plant extracts, plant oils, vitamins E and A, and preservatives. This is a good lightweight moisturizer for around the eyes-if you aren't allergic to gold. It claims to lighten circles around the eyes, but nothing in this product can perform that function. Sometimes keeping the skin around the eye moist can help soften the appearance of dark circles, but any moisturizer can do the same thing.<BR>
24 Karat Skin Treatment Serum ($39.95 for 7 ampoules) contains mostly, water, aloe, alcohol, AHA, slip agents, thickeners, and preservatives. This is nothing more than a lightweight AHA product packaged in tiny vials that make it outrageously expensive to use. Alcohol is a mistake in skin-care products, and except for the gold there is nothing about this product that warrants any further attention.</I><P>
<P>
Dear Paula,<BR>
I am writing to thank you for your efforts in helping women sort out their skin-care woes. Since adolescence, I have always had a few pimples here and there, but nothing to get too excited about. However, I am in my mid-30s now, and for the last five years or so I have been struggling with breakouts, constant breakouts. I have tried all sorts of skin-care products, I have been to dermatologists, I have tried Retin-A, I have tried herbal medicine taken internally, etc. I don't smoke, I don't drink more than a beer or so a week, I run 15 miles a week, I drink plenty of fluids, I take daily vitamins, I eat a healthy diet, I sleep well, etc. I just couldn't get rid of those breakouts; it has been extremely frustrating. To add to the complexity of the situation, I live in New England, where the climate changes swiftly; one day can be humid and the next day can be bone dry. And lastly, I am Asian, living in a predominantly Caucasian population that seems to think collectively that I should have "tougher" skin than they do. My husband uses rubbing alcohol as aftershave and thinks alcohol should be an appropriate toner for me!
Now, all things considered, thank goodness, life has been very kind to me. I am blessed with a wonderful family, good health, a good job, and happiness in general. But, being an engineer by trade and a perfectionist by nature, this acne battle has been quite resource consuming. Well, with the help of your books, I finally figured out my skin problem. (By the way, I found out about your books on the Internet.) See, every "expert" thought I had oily skin. Unfortunately, I also have very sensitive skin. So, while I was trying to stop the breakouts, the acne products that were prescribed or recommended to me were destroying my skin. I had a bout of eczema a couple of years ago after using a dermatologist's own brand of products. 
So, I tried your products for normal to dry skin, and guess what: my face actually feels pretty good. I mean, no tingling, no itching, and no new breakouts! I have also started using an SPF 35 cream every day. Anyway, after boring you to tears, I want to thank you again. Hopefully, my "dry" skin will calm down in the long run. <BR>
Eva, via e-mail (who has to look for something else to spend time and money on, now that my skin-care search is coming to an end!)<P>

<I>Dear Eva,<BR>
What a great note! Your story is outstanding. It is unfortunate that most people still believe that when you see a blemish you have to dry it up! Nothing could be further from the truth. Drying up acne, no matter what kind of skin you have, only makes matters worse by causing the skin to flake more, which causes more dead skin cells to fill up and block pores. What a vicious cycle. It's best to use a little 3% hydrogen peroxide or 2.5% benzoyl peroxide (ProActiv's is very good) over blemishes to disinfect them. That will help a lot. </I><P>
<P>
Dear Paula,<BR> 
A couple of months ago I saw an infomercial about a product called Sweet Simplicity. I ordered this hair-removal system because it claimed not to be like typical wax-based hair removers. After using it only one time, I decided it was no different than any other product I used to remove hair. Perhaps I was not using it correctly. Any thoughts about Sweet Simplicity?<BR>
Peggy, Englewood, CO<P>

<I>Dear Peggy,<BR>
My only thought about Sweet Simplicity is that it is neither simple or sweet. Well, that's not entirely true. It may taste sweet, but of course you're not supposed to eat this product. Sweet Simplicity, a sugar-based hair remover with a consistency like caramel, differs from wax only in content. Its performance is identical to most other wax products I've ever seen. Like any product that you spread on the skin and then rip off to remove hair, it can be messy, it can cause irritation, and the rate of grow-back is identical to waxing. The infomercial women gushing with amazement at Sweet Simplicity's performance are being more than a little disingenuous. Not that it can't remove hair well-it can-but so can any wax product. They just aren't mentioning all the drawbacks that can go with this kind of product. If you can deal with the mess it is an option, but it is not the wonder product the infomercial makes it out to be.</I><P>

<P>
Dear Paula,<BR>
Well, I've finally had enough of your [garbage]. For the past year I've had to endure hearing you on TV babbling on like you know what you are talking about. I've had to pass your book when I've been looking for some real literature. Now I have something to say to you. It is your right to have an opinion about the hair-care industry and its products. Also true is the fact that it is only an opinion. You are by no means an expert on hair-care products or the industry. You are not a professional stylist who makes his or her living by using these products to create art, style, and beauty. <BR>
Part of my job is to make people feel good about the way they look. I know for a fact I cannot do that with Pert Plus or Salon Selectives. Have you spent any time with a hair-care professional? Oh no, that would be the right thing to do: get a full idea of what the industry is all about. Why would you actually want to get a broad spectrum of information before you shoot your mouth off? Did you talk to clients who use professional products and who used to use drugstore products? You talked to chemical engineers who broke down the products for you. Funny, did they break down the crappy drugstore ones too? You say the hair cannot be repaired because it's dead. Funny, why can't it? Can't protein bond with protein to help reform and repair? <BR>
Before you peddle your poison, maybe you should spend some time in the research facilities of some great hair-care companies like Joico or Matrix, people who spend vast quantities of money to constantly improve the tools I use to make my living. It's one thing to have an informed, full-bodied, widely researched, and unbiased opinion; it's another to spout off to sell books. Think of that the next time you're doing your dated do.<BR>
Michael, via e-mail<P>

<I>Dear Michael,<BR>
What a shame you are so angry that you can't see the forest for the trees. I spent many years working with hairstylists, and I have the deepest respect for their ability and work. I make that point crystal-clear in my book and whenever I appear on a talk show. My comments about professional hair-care products do not reflect on the professionals using them. After all, you are not involved with their formulation, you are only trained by the companies selling them. When the only information you have is from the manufacturer, naturally it is limited, or, at the very least, one-sided. 
When I did the research for my hair-care book I talked to the top cosmetic chemists formulating these products for both expensive and inexpensive hair-care lines, as well as to department heads of cosmetic chemistry at both the University of Texas and the University of Cincinnati. I read a great deal of the published research and a number of technical books on hair, including The Chemical and Physical Behavior of Human Hair by Clarence Robbins, one of the more respected chemists in the business. I interviewed at length the cosmetic chemists at Paul Mitchell, Revlon, Clairol, and L'Oreal. (Revlon, Clairol, and L'Oreal also make so-called professional products; for example, Clairol owns Matrix, and L'Oreal, which holds more hair-care patents than any other company, now owns Redken.) I also interviewed more than a hundred hairstylists from salons across the country. What I found, repeatedly, was that these artists knew an immense about styling but very little about product content, either within the lines they sold or in lines from the drugstore. They had preconceived notions about hair and hair-care products that simply were not correct or had no substantiation anywhere.
I have spent years doing research, and my area of expertise is product content and what is possible when it comes to hair growth and hair damage. I can tell you about the molecular as well as the texture and performance differences between most hair-care ingredients, in addition to the composition and nature of hair. For example, there are no published studies that indicate that proteins or amino acids can bond to hair or have any capacity for getting into the hair shaft and staying there. According to most of the researchers I have talked to (actually, all of them, but some were off the record), protein and amino acids, like "botanical" ingredients, are there for the consumer and not the hair. 
I know my information is shocking at times, but it is substantiated by mountains of research. If you could show me even one published study that supports your contentions, I would be glad to correct my position. In regard to your remark about the chemical analysis of hair-care products, both inexpensive and expensive products were investigated, and I did not have anything to do with that experiment. It was conducted by an independent lab hired by producers  of the Prime Time Live show I appeared on.
</I><P>
<P>
Dear Paula,<BR>
I have two teenage daughters. I have used your books and newsletter almost like a bible. Your tips and research have saved me lots of money buying for three women. All three of us are aware of how important the right shade of foundation is. However, each time one of my daughters' friends buys a new brand, they want to use a new brand too. So many companies in the inexpensive price range do not have testers or samples. And when has department-store lighting ever matched the lighting outside? My question to you is, Have you ever thought of matching colors from amongst the varying lines of cosmetics? (For example, Lancome MaquiDouceur Beige Neutral matches Revlon Age Defying Foundation Bare Buff.) This would be a fantastic chart to follow in cross-referencing the same shade in different lines.<BR>
Also, I recently became allergic to nail polish. My dermatologist suggested I use only those that are hypoallergenic. Any suggestions?
And as long as I have your attention, what do you think of the Glycolique line of skin-care products that is sweeping the salons in my area?<BR>
Keena, Corsicana, TX<P>

<I>Dear Keena,<BR>
Luring you with the promise of the next great product is what the cosmetics industry is all about. Teenagers are particularly vulnerable to this pressure because they are both absolutely certain they know just what is best for them and utterly insecure about their decisions. This constant imbalance is completely baffling to adults. I can't tell you how often I've run into a teenager with thick heavy makeup, a distinct line around her jaw and hairline, and a caked gummy mess around her nose and under-eye area, yet when I point it out to her with a mirror in daylight she simply doesn't see it, informing me that this is a very expensive foundation and some well-known actress or model wears it too. (I should mention that adults do this too.) Teens are notoriously susceptible to advertising or advice from friends that entices them to immediately change what they are doing, and also to advertising or advice that urges them to stand steadfast despite the evidence clearly in front of them. Please help your daughters remain strong in their choices and reaffirm that what's important in life has little or nothing to do with someone else having it better than you do, because sometimes what appears to be better isn't, and what's better for someone else may not be best for you. <BR>
Although I think that charting foundation comparisons is a great suggestion, the task would be more complicated and time consuming than you could ever imagine. The nuances in colors are vast, and the number of foundations per line, sometimes a half-dozen types with 12 to 24 shades per type, make charting even two different lines a colossal nightmare. Besides, regardless of the similarity between two shades, formula differences affect the color once it is blended on real skin. <BR>
In regard to finding a hypoallergenic nail polish, tell your doctor none exists. In fact, the concept hypoallergenic doesn't really exist in the world of cosmetics. I thought this misleading term was long dead. Where has your dermatologist been? He or she must think that "hypoallergenic" has some kind of meaning in the cosmetics world, and nothing could be further from the truth. There is nothing that makes any particular line or product more hypoallergenic than any other. Finding products you are not allergic to is a matter of searching and experimenting, especially when it comes to nail polishes, because the formulas and ingredients are so similar.
Glycolique sells an interesting trio of products. Refine Step 1 ($19.95 for 4 ounces) is nothing more than a toner that contains slip agents, plant extract, plant oil, and preservatives. It isn't a bad toner, just OK. Algae and seaweed provide no real benefit other than sales appeal. Retexturize Step 2 ($39.95 for 2.5 ounces) is an alcohol-based AHA product that is probably 6% to 7% AHA. I do not recommend alcohol for any skin type, and definitely not when using an AHA product. Restore Step 3 ($27.95 for 1 ounce) is a good moisturizing AHA product with about the same AHA concentration as Step 2. This one is best for someone with dry skin. However, I would never suggest that all three are necessary; one AHA product is all anyone's skin needs. I should mention that without a separate sunscreen product, these three steps would not be enough for anyone's skin. Glycolique's number is (800) 704-9277.</I><P>

Dear Paula,<BR>
Please tell me what you think of the Tyra products I am using. I would really appreciate your feedback. They aren't all that expensive, but I just wonder if they are really helping my skin or if I could be doing better.<BR>
Helen, Dallas, TX<P>

<I>Dear Helen,<BR>
Without knowing your skin type or what you expect from the products you are using, I can only comment generally on the Tyra line of skin-care products, based on the formulas. I do find it puzzling that you think these products are attractively priced, but I imagine price is relative depending on what you are used to buying. <BR>
Tyra's brochure carries on about the skin's need for water: "Both the medical community and the cosmetic industry agree that loss of water is the leading cause of most skin problems." That is not an accurate statement. Dehydration causes dry skin, but few other skin problems. Acne, sun damage, pigmentation changes, sensitivities, allergies, and so on are the cause of most skin problems, and they have nothing to do with dehydration. At several points the copy explains that Tyra products will not clog pores. Tyra needs to check their ingredient lists more closely, because their products contain ingredients that definitely could cause problems for some skin types.<BR>
Phase I, Premier  Cleanser ($15 for 8 ounces) is a standard detergent-based cleanser that also has a foaming agent. It also contains lanolin oil and jojoba oil, which can clog pores. This would be appropriate only for someone with extremely dry skin, if the cleansing agents did not feel drying.<BR>
Phase II, Premier  Normalizer ($15 for 8 ounces) is a good but extremely standard toner that contains mostly slip agents, soothing agents, and water-binding agent. That's fine, but unimpressive.<BR>
Phase III, Premier  Moisturizer ($36 for 4 ounces) contains mostly water, thickeners, plant oil, more thickeners, and preservatives. It is a good moisturizer for someone with dry skin, but the price is absurd. This is so standard it's almost a joke.<BR>
Plus IV Deep Moisturizer ($44 for 4 ounces) contains water, plant oil, thickeners, a tiny amount of vitamins, soothing agent, more thickeners, and preservatives. It is an emollient but rather standard moisturizer. The only thing wrong with it is the price.<BR>
Hand/Body Lotion ($12 for 8 ounces) contains mostly water, thickeners, water-binding agent, soothing agent, and preservatives. It would be fine for someone with normal to slightly dry skin, but it's nothing special.<BR>
Luxury Shower/Bath Gelee ($12 for 8 ounces) is just shampoo with standard detergent cleansing agents and foaming agents. This one contains sodium lauryl sulfate, which can be drying and potentially irritating for the skin.
</I><P>

<P>
Dear Paula,<BR>
Lancome has a toner, Eau De Bienfait, that you did not review in the new edition of your book. It is supposedly a cleansing toner with vitamins for the face and eyes. Does this help? And, of course, the eternal question: Is it worth the money?
<BR>
Janna, via e-mail
<P>

<I>Dear Janna,<BR>
Lancome Eau de Bienfait ($22.50 for 6.8 ounces) is a good but remarkably ordinary toner that contains mostly water, lightweight detergent cleansing agents, slip agent, tiny amounts of vitamins E and A, fragrance, and preservatives. As an extra cleansing step it is just fine, but the vitamins won't improve or help skin. This can be considered an antioxidant product, but the amount of antioxidants is minuscule and their effectiveness is unproven regardless of the amount. </I><P>

<P>
Dear Paula,<BR>
I love your skepticism, I love your books, and I love your contributions to womankind! I'd like to share my personal horror story with you and your readers so they can be forewarned. <BR>
I'd always had extremely oily skin. I had a few breakouts a month, but my acne was mild. By my mid-20s it wasn't so bad at all. In fact, it was great, but by my late 20s I noticed some scars around my mouth near the chin, and some tiny ones on my cheeks. These scars really bothered me. I went to a plastic surgeon and requested a mild acid peel. He said that it wouldn't do anything. He said that light dermabrasion would work. So I was dermabraded. <BR>
Initially the results were thrilling, because my skin was perfect (if very pink). However, within the next six weeks, the swelling went down and I was dismayed to find every single flaw was not only still there, but worse! Also, the texture of my skin was sort of rough and grainy, and I scarred much more readily after the procedure. I cried for a whole year. I went back to the doctor and asked him to fix my skin. Again I requested a mild acid peel. Again he said that it wouldn't do anything, but he told me to come back a week later. I said that I had only four days to recover, so I didn't want anything too deep. <BR>
He gave me a phenol peel. It was really a horror show for about two weeks and somewhat scary for the next two weeks. It is hard to describe what it feels like to go from attractive to monstrous in the course of ten minutes, but that is what happened to me. I wanted to die when I realized that all those big holes in my face wouldn't just go away. In short, this procedure made me a million times worse. I looked like I had a disease. It was really horrible.<BR>
That was almost three years ago. Over the last three years, I have faithfully used my Retin-A, AHA, and avoided the sun. I have lost my faith in the medical profession. I had never heard of anyone being made to be as ugly as this doctor made me. I'm more normal-looking now. With the new CO2 ultra-pure laser, I had hope, so I made a few appointments with other doctors. I learned some interesting things.<BR>
The doctor who destroyed my face had a reputation for messing people up, even though he was board certified, but no one did anything about it. Apparently it took him about ten years to pass the board.<BR>
Doctors rarely, if ever, perform these procedures on thick, oily-skinned individuals because they do not work. I learned that I was not a candidate for even one pass with the CO2 laser.<BR>
All I could do was try a series of glycolic peels in addition to my usual routine. Another doctor suggested that I could wait a year for the YAG laser, which has a depth of necrosis about one-quarter that of the CO2 laser and is therefore much safer and less likely to scar. "But," he said, "it won't make much of a difference. You will never be happy with your skin. You can try the YAG, if you want to spend some money. It might tighten up the pores a little bit. Or you can try some glycolic peels. They might help."<BR>
So you see, I need all the help I can get. Every time I look in the mirror, I want to cry. I have a great job. I meet with professors and engineering consultants. I give presentations. It's important to look competent and good. I don't want to cringe when these people get within a yard of my face! I completely lost my confidence when I lost parts of my reticular dermis. As I said, it's not as bad as I am making it sound, but it is so much worse than my initial condition. <BR>
Please let this be a warning to any and all who are interested in these procedures. Please do not use my name. <BR>
Olive Skin and Depressed
<P><I>
Dear Olive Skin,<BR>
I am sad to hear you had such a devastating experience. I appreciate that you took the time to share your story with me and with my readers. I would also like to warn my readers that deep acne scarring is one of the most difficult skin conditions to correct, and the results from both dermabrasion and laser surgery can pose a great deal of risk or potential damage, along with minimal improvement. Any physician who promises results for this type of corrective procedure should be avoided. <BR>
In regard to plastic surgery, let me add one more concern. The trend these days for face-lifts is to do everything at once: specifically, having a face-lift and laser surgery at the same time. Several plastic surgeons I spoke to said they would never do a complete face-lift and a laser peel at the same time. When both procedures are done concurrently, you could easily end up with what I call the "Beverly Hills Pull"-skin pulled so tight the face looks strange, as if a smile and a wide-eyed expression were permanently embedded into the skin. <BR>
You ask for help, but I'm not sure how I can be of assistance. You didn't mention whether you need advice regarding skin care, makeup, or other potential surgeries. In the meantime, be aware that there are many ways to excel in the world. Some do it with beauty, some with brains, some with brawn, and some with style, as well as combinations thereof. In my opinion, and I monitor many aspects of beauty, the most powerful combination of all is brains and style, and that has little to do with physical beauty.</I><P>
<P>
Dear Paula,<BR>
What do you think of the Earth Preserv line of products?<BR>
Gaylene, Friendwood, TX<P>
<I>
Dear Gaylene,<BR>
I think the marketing for Earth Preserv products is far more interesting than the products themselves. This line of hair and body products has more to do with fragrance than product choice. The Shampoo ($9.50 for 8.8 ounces), Hair Vitalizer (conditioner) ($9.50 for 8.8 ounces), Nourishing Body Bath ($9.50 for 8.8 ounces), Skin Moisturizer ($9.50 for 8.8 ounces), and Bath Crystals ($7 for 8.8 ounces) come in four very attractive scents: Autumn Woodlands, Summer Nectar, Spring Petals, and Winter Snowmelt. Also, all of the products are packaged in recyclable aluminum. Earth Preserv's brochure accurately states that plastic is a poor recyclable because the process is fairly costly, while over 70% of aluminum packaging is recycled. From that standpoint Earth Preserv is indeed earth friendly. But what about product performance?<BR>
Earth Preserv's claims that their products are "all natural" are fairly exaggerated. For example, they explain that their shampoos are superior to others because instead of sulfate detergent cleansing agents they use decyl and lauryl polyglucose and plant extracts. Decyl and lauryl polyglucose do not grow on trees, and there isn't even all that much plant extract in the shampoo. Their extremely beautiful catalog (more about this below) states that "natural means the pure substance or a natural derivative ?such as cetearyl alcohol from coconut oil." The brochure never explains how you get cetearyl alcohol from coconut oil. That process is most unnatural, and cetearyl alcohol does not resemble anything having to do with a coconut.<BR>
The oils used in the Hair Vitalizer aren't bad for the hair, but silicone oil, which they claim is unnatural, is more effective. (They do note that silicone oil can build up on hair, which is true, but that should not be a problem, especially if you alternate shampoos occasionally.) Both the Shampoo and the Hair Vitalizer contain clove oil and bergamot oil, which can irritate the eyes, so be careful. <BR>
Earth Preserv professes disdain for collagen and cholesterol because they come from animals; however, that is rarely the case anymore. These ingredients are now derived mostly from plant sources. Also, if one more cosmetics company claims that petrolatum causes breakouts, I'm going to scream. That is simply unfounded, and I've never found any proof otherwise in any research on acne. However, I've seen plenty of research that indicates jojoba oil can aggravate acne, and it is the fifth ingredient in the Skin Moisturizer.<BR>
Many of Earth Preserv's warnings are valid-for instance, it is true that sodium olefin sulfate and sodium lauryl sulfate are drying detergent cleansing agents that can strip hair color-but plenty of other companies also leave these ingredients out of their products. <BR>
In short, Earth Preserv products aren't bad, but the hair-care products are best for someone with normal to slightly dry hair and scalp or someone with thin or fine hair. They would be a problem for someone with dry, damaged, coarse, or thick hair, or someone who uses a lot of styling products. The bath products are fine if you like the fragrances, and the Skin Moisturizer is OK too, but only if you don't tend to break out. <BR>
Despite my criticisms, I must admit that the Earth Preserv catalog is stunning, with a wonderful array of bath products, including votive candles, bathrobes, towels, a beautiful slate fountain, one-of-a-kind picture frames, and other alluring items. If you are looking for some intriguing holiday gifts, this may be the place to shop. Earth Preserv's phone number is (800) 9-EARTH9. </I><P>
<P>
Dear Paula,<BR>
I have come across another cosmetics line that looks tempting. Before I leap, I want your opinion. A lot of celebrities are apparently flocking to get their hands on these items. Please tell me about Vita-A-Kombi 1, Karin Herzog's Mild Scrub, and Karin Herzog's Soft Cleansing Milk.<BR>
Anne, Douglaston, NY<P>
<I>Dear Anne,<BR>
Don't all cosmetics look tempting? And aren't there always gaggles of celebrities doing such a wide variety of things to their faces and bodies that it would be impossible to follow everything they do in hopes of picking up their beauty secrets? I know we all think that whatever someone rich and famous does to her skin must be the best, but having seen what a number of celebrities use when it comes to makeup and skin care, I can honestly say that is not the case. <BR>
In regard to the products, the Vit-A-Kombi 1 ($50 for 1.76 ounces) seems like a bad joke. It contains mostly water, petrolatum, mineral oil, glycerin, thickener, hydrogen peroxide, vitamin A, and preservatives. This is a good moisturizer, but the amount of vitamin A in here is minuscule at best, and hydrogen peroxide is not stable in a cosmetic (that's why it comes packaged in a dark brown bottle; it deteriorates when exposed to air).<BR>
The Mild Scrub ($35 for 2.12 ounces) is just a mild abrasive (using marble powder) in a bunch of grease. At $35 it is absurd. You would be better off mixing a small amount of baking soda with Cetaphil cleanser (available at the drugstore for $8 for 16 ounces). <BR>
The Soft Cleansing Milk ($35 for 7.14 ounces) is just an average cleanser that is terribly overpriced. It is appropriate only for someone with very dry skin who doesn't want to get all her makeup off.</I><P>
<P>
Dear Paula,<BR>
I recently purchased your third edition of Don't Go to the Cosmetics Counter Without Me, and it is great. I also read your recent issue of Cosmetics Counter Update and was surprised by your comments on your own makeup. You stated that you used to wear blush and lipstick in both warm and cool tones. I thought you were a strong advocate of the "seasonal" color theory that says we should wear either warm or cool colors but not both. Do you feel that most of us can wear either one? I have been told that I have "warm" coloring, but I like rose much better than coral. As always, thanks for your expertise.<BR>
Mary, via e-mail<P>
<I>Dear Mary,<BR>
I am indeed very pro the seasonal concept of colors, but there are exceptions to every rule. Although I generally look best in cool cosmetics colors, I found that I could also wear salmon shades for a softer, more "natural" look. Salmon is kind of a cool/warm color because it takes pink and yellow to make salmon. Finding a makeup style that looks good takes experimentation, and it never hurts to find out if breaking the rules will work for you. In my case, I found that I can wear neutral/warm colors on my eyes and cheeks as long as I wear a more richly colored lipstick, usually a true red. As it turns out, that is pretty much a classic makeup look. Only the younger models wear neutral shades all over.</I><P>
<P>
Dear Paula,<BR>
I am enclosing as much information as I could gather on the Balenare Skin Care System, which I am currently using and from which I seem to be getting good results. My question is whether this line of cosmetics, which is not inexpensive, meets your standards of quality as well as competitive pricing. I have been blessed with good skin and did not have any problems with products I was formerly using. <BR>
Rita, Carrollton, TX<P>
<I>Dear Rita,<BR>
I am always hesitant to review a product line when a woman tells me she is getting good results from it. Half the battle in skin care, besides knowing what's in the products you are using, is finding what works for you. Both are difficult tasks. Still, it is hard for me to not be shocked and exasperated by the prices of the products you are using. In fact, the entire premise for this product line is inane. For example, the notion that "dermaplaq" is bad for the skin is just plain silly. This term must have been made up by Balenare's marketing people, because it does not appear in any of the professional journals I have been researching for years and none of the dermatologists I've spoken to have heard of it. <BR>
The notion that cosmetic buildup exists and that it is dangerous for the skin is bizarre. Definitely, if you don't clean your skin, makeup can build up, but even the simplest skin-care routine can take care of that problem. And, yes, skin cells can accumulate for some skin types (for example, sun-damaged skin, dry skin, or oily skin), but that problem is easily handled by simple cleansing and using an exfoliant, such as an AHA product or even a washcloth. It doesn't takes a $200 skin-care routine. Furthermore, any skin-care line that touts such miracles but doesn't include an SPF 15 product as part of their primary skin-care routine is uninformed. <BR>
Here are my comments on the Balenare skin-care products. <BR>
Cleansing Lotion contains mostly water, thickeners, plant extracts, plant oil, thickeners, detergent cleansing agents, more thickeners, and preservatives. The minuscule amounts of vitamins are almost silly, but there are enough oils to cause buildup on the skin. Jojoba oil in particular can clog pores.<BR>
Buffing Creme is a standard cleansing cream that contains papaya and salicylic acid. It is an OK exfoliant, but I am not fond of recommending these two ingredients for exfoliating the skin. It also contains mint and lemon, which can be skin irritants.<BR>
Orange Papaya Cleansing Gel is a standard detergent cleanser that lists sodium lauryl sulfate as the second ingredient. That makes it a fairly strong cleanser that can be too drying for most skin types. By the way, I am not surprised Balenare suggests washing with this after you wash with the Cleansing Lotion; you may need another cleanser to remove the greasy residue left by the Cleansing Lotion.<BR>
Aqua Freshener is just water, witch hazel, alum (like a styptic pencil), boric acid, plant extracts, and preservatives. Witch hazel can be a skin irritant and alum can be drying. This product would be appropriate only for someone with oily skin, and even then I probably wouldn't recommend it.<BR>
Face Value (Dermaplaq Free) contains mostly water, several thickeners, papaya (as an exfoliant), plant oil, more thickeners, more plant oils, vitamins, silicone oil, water-binding agent, salicylic acid, plant extracts, tiny amounts of more water-binding agents, and preservatives. This is an emollient moisturizer that also contains exfoliants. It's fine, but only one exfoliating product is needed in any skin-care routine.<BR>
Perfect Balance P.M. contains mostly thickeners, plant oils, vitamins, water-binding agent, plant extracts, and preservatives. This is a good moisturizer for dry skin, but that's about it. By the way, this product lists liposomes as an ingredient, which is misleading. Liposomes are a delivery system, a way of formulating a product, not a specific ingredient.<BR>
Maximum Day Care is similar to the product above, but with a tiny amount of sunscreen. Without an SPF 15, this is useless for daytime.</I><P>
<P>
Dear Paula,<BR>
My daughter has both of your books and I was looking over the new edition the other day. I was surprised to read your review of the only product I have been loyal to for over six years Clarins Skin Firming Concentrate. I started using this product at the recommendation of my best friend. At the time she was about to celebrate her 40th birthday. Her friends and her husband's family all thought it was her 30th. She had no wrinkles at all, and her eye area was as firm as a teenager's. She told me that she had been using the Clarins Concentrate for many years. <BR>
I had major frown lines between my eyebrows that I couldn't stand. Before I used up the first jar of the Serum, the lines had all but disappeared. I started using it all around my eyes. As I approached 40 years old, I began noticing the feathering of my lipstick. I remember my mom using many different products to try to stop it. I started using this product on my lips, and within a few weeks the feathering disappeared totally! I am 41 years old and pregnant with my fifth child. Many people tell me I look too young to have five children, and they are even more amazed to hear that my oldest is 15! I am constantly being told that I look like I am in my early 30s. I am positive that the Clarins Skin Firming Concentrate is the reason why. <BR>
It is obvious from your comments about this product that you never bothered to actually test it or talk to someone who has been using it. Unless you are going to give a product a fair review, it should not be included in your book!<BR>
Suzanne, Santa Maria, CA <P>
<I>Dear Suzanne,<BR>
I make it very clear in my book that I do not review products from experience but rather from formulation versus claims. If a product contains standard cosmetic ingredients but makes elaborate claims about eliminating wrinkles, or if it contains potentially irritating ingredients but claims to be good for sensitive skin, and so on, I point that out.<BR>
I believe my reviews to be completely fair. I have never said that using a moisturizer would not improve the appearance of skin. However, in no way can the ingredients in the Clarins product cure wrinkles. It is just not humanly, or should I say cosmetically, possible. This product doesn't contain anything that doesn't show up in a thousand other products making the same claim. And, actually, this formulation is rather dated and lacks a lot of the new skin-care ingredients that may work even better in terms of smoothing the skin. What do you make of the 10,000 other anti-wrinkle products on the market; are they all unreliable and Clarins the only answer? And what about Clarins' other anti-wrinkle products; if they are also capable of living up to their claims about wrinkles, why be loyal to just this one?<BR>
It is clear you have found a product that works well for you, and that is great. You are completely at liberty to believe whatever you want to. You don't have to agree with my review, but the information is solid and backed up with an immense amount of research and substantiation from cosmetic chemists at universities and cosmetics companies all over the country.</I> <P>
<HR>

  <TITLE>Spotted Penis Mystery</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<P><B>SPOTTED PENIS MYSTERY</B></P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<P>Dear Alice,</P>

<P>I know that having intercourse at a time when I have a vaginal infection
will cause my partner to become infected, i.e., red spots on the penis.
 What could cause him to get this when I'm not having any symptoms?<BR>
<BR>
</P>

<P><HR ALIGN=LEFT><BR>
</P>

<P>Red spots on the penis could be caused by an allergic reaction to the
spermicidal jelly or cream you are using for contraception, or by the nonoxynol
or lubricant that is on condoms.  Red spots can also be caused by something
that you have that is asymptomatic in you.  It sounds as if you are already
on the case, and now have some variables to test as well.  There also seems
to be sufficient reason to get yourself, and your partner, checked for STDs
(sexually transmitted diseases).  If you are a Columbia student, you can
make an appointment with Health Services by calling x4-2284, then pressing
2.  If you are not a Columbia student, you can go to the nearest city or
county health department's STD clinic (they usually have  a great deal of
experience with STDs), or to your own private doctor.  </P>

<P>Good luck on your search for the solution to the spotted penis mystery.<BR>
<BR>
</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<DL>
  <DD><A HREF="../about.html"><I>Alice</I></A>
</DL>

<P>&nbsp;</P>

<H4>December 6, 1996</H4>
</BODY>
</HTML>
