<html>

<head>
<category=1; number=0861>
<title>Testing for asymptomatic herpes</title>
</head>

<body>
<h3>Herpes testing</h3>
<br>
Dear Alice,

<p>
<i>Question one:</i><p>
This service is a God-send. I feel more informed than I did a few 
days ago. 
<p>
I have a few questions regarding Herpes Simplex 2. Can you be tested 
for the virus even if an active sore is NOT present? And what are the 
signs to know if the virus is shedding even if there are no sores or 
related pain?
<br>
-- Want to be safe
<br>
<p>

<i>Question two:</i><p>
My ex-girlfriend had (has) genital herpes. We always used condoms, 
and never had sex during outbreaks. I don't have any symptoms, but 
am worried about possibly being asymptomatic. I want to start new 
relationships, but I'm reluctant because I don't know what to tell 
new partners. Is there a reliable test for asymptomatic people? --
<br>
-- Anxious to resume
<br>
<hr>
<br>

<p>Dear Want to be safe & Anxious to resume,<p>

In view of herpes frequently asymptomatic state, the ease of 
passing it to someone else, along with the general regard (however 
questionable) in this society that herpes is a bad thing to have, 
people want to know if they have been infected. Through the many 
similar questions that are asked, Alice understands your concern. 
Unfortunately the news is that there is not currently a <i>useful</i> 
blood test for herpes simplex virus type 2, the most common cause 
of genital herpes.
<p>
Any reasonably comprehensive laboratory can offer herpes antibody 
testing. That sounds like what's needed, right?  Well, the problem 
here is that it's a bad test. There is a marked overlap between its 
ability to detect
antibodies (immune proteins that are part of the body's defense 
system against specific infections) to type 1 (the main cause of oral 
herpes) and type 2. That is, many adults, an estimated 50-90%, 
acquired type 1 infection in childhood as an oral or throat infection. 
Many of these people will appear to have positive antibodies on the 
current test against type 2 herpes.  So a positive antibody test for 
herpes type 2 is unreliable. And to make things even harder, type 1 
herpes can certainly cause genital infection.
<p>
Twenty to thirty percent of U.S. adults are believed to have herpes
type 2 antibodies. That percent is pretty high. Without doubt, the 
majority of that large number are unaware of being infected. In a  
study done in a STD clinic, clinicians found that 60% of infected 
women never had any symptoms and another 16% had no recent 
symptoms. Are they all contagious? How contagious?  Were some 
never contagious? We just don't know the answers to these 
questions.
<p>
Asymptomatic signs or viral shedding would be very difficult to 
determine, although some people can tell before an outbreak is about 
to occur...they feel more irritable, on edge, and may have a tingling 
or itching sensation at the site where the blister is going to form.
<p>
Herpes is not the worst thing in the world, and the current 
unsatisfactory state of testing will change.  Try not to be overly 
concerned.  In each of your situations, it is likely that you are not 
infected or that you developed a strong immune response early in 
your life or after you became sexually active.  Alice would advise 
you, however, to continue practicing sex in safe ways and discussing 
the many reasons you do so with your future partners. Whether or not 
you or a partner is infected with herpes, many other, more serious 
sexually transmitted diseases don't show any symptoms, either.

<p>
<dl>
<dd><a href="about.html"><i>Alice</i></a>
</dl>

<p>
<h4>April 5, 1996</h4>
<p>

</body>
</html>

HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Tue, 07 Jan 1997 17:31:28 GMT

</DOCHDR>
<html>
<category=1; number=0648>
<title>
Urinary Tract Infection
</title>
<h3>
Urinary Tract Infection
</h3>
<br>
Alice, I think I may have some kind of urinary tract infection. It came on very suddenly, about three nights ago. And when I pee, there is a burning sensation when my bladder has almost emptied. It's not an STD because I'm in a monogamous relationship, and yes, I'm sure! Please help. Thank you. --Burning Up

<hr>
<br>
<p>Dear Burning Up,<br>
Urinary tract infections(UTIs) are so common that most women get at least one at some point in their lives. They are usually caused by bacteria, such as E. coli, which travel from the colon to the urethra and bladder (and occasionally the kidneys). Trichomoniasis and chlamydia can also cause UTIs; stress, low resistance, poor diet, damage to the urethra from childbirth, surgery, etc., can predispose you to getting them. Often a sudden increase in sexual activity triggers a case of "honeymoon cystitis", or urinary tract infection. 

<p>Cystitis is the most common form of UTI. While the symptoms may scare you, it is rarely serious if treated. Symptoms include:
<UL>
<LI>feeling like you need to urinate every few minutes
<LI>burning like crazy when you try to urinate
<LI>many times, hardly any urine comes out
<LI>possibly blood in the urine
<LI>sometimes pain just above your pubic bone
<LI>sometimes a peculiar odor to your first urine in the morning
</UL>
<p>To prevent UTIs, treat mild infections and avoid reinfections, try the following self-help measures:
<UL>
<LI>Drink lots of fluids every day.
<LI>Urinate frequently and try to empty your bladder completely each time.
<LI>Wipe yourself from front to back after urinating and moving your bowels, trying to keep the bacteria in your bowels away from your urethra.
<LI>You and your partner should clean your hands before having sex, and after contact with the anal area before touching the vagina.
<LI>Make sure you are well-lubricated before intercourse.
<LI>Empty your bladder before and after sex.
<LI>Change sanitary napkins frequently during your period.
<LI>Wear loose clothing.
<LI>Cut down on caffeine and alcohol. With an active infection, eliminate both. 
<LI>Cut down on sweets.
<LI>Drink unsweetened cranberry juice.
<LI>Eat well and get enough rest. 
<LI>Keep your stress levels down, if possible.
</UL>
<p>When a UTI doesn't respond to self-help treatment within 24 hours or recurs frequently, see a medical provider. Treatment is usually with antibiotics, and a drug called Pyridium, which will relieve the pain and turn your urine a bright orange. Untreated UTIs can lead to serious infections of the kidneys, so if pain and symptoms persist, make sure you see a provider.

<p>At Columbia, if you think you have a urinary tract infection, make an appointment at Women's Health by calling 4-2284. Outside the University, see your regular medical provider or gynecologist. 
<p>
<dd><a href="about.html"><i>Alice</i></a>
<p>
<h4>May 8, 1995</h4>
<p>
</html>

<DOCNO>WTX020-B05-398</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA021-000226-B002-302</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.columbia.edu:80/cu/healthwise/0473.html 128.59.35.58 19970107173506 text/html 2404
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Tue, 07 Jan 1997 17:35:10 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
Content-length: 2233
Last-modified: Tue, 03 Jan 1995 15:38:34 GMT
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<category=1; number=0473>
<title>
Urinary tract infection?
</title>
<h3>
Urinary tract infection?
</h3>
<br>
Dear Alice,
<p>      For the second time this year, I have had a bout of what I think 
      might be a u-tract infection, but I'm not sure if that's what it 
      is. For about a week now I have had the urgency to urinate 
      hundreds of times throughout the day, and could easily urinate 
      every five minutes without problem. The bothersome thing is that, 
      although I'm not incontinent, it is dripping a little and is 
      therefore very unpleasant and awkward. I'm not experiencing any 
      burning sensation, and I know that I'm not pregnant. Any advice? 
      (I started drinking cranberry juice yesterday, thinking that might 
      help I'm not exactly sure why).
<p>      Thanks,
<br>      Slightly embarrassed.

<hr>
<br>
Dear Slightly embarrassed, 

<p>There are any number of causes of the symptoms you're 
      experiencing. You need to have a culture done to determine the 
      exact cause and appropriate treatment. It is not a good idea to 
      leave this type of infection untreated, because it can spread 
      through other parts of your body, sometimes asymptomatically. 
      Please walk-in to health services before you leave for break, or 
      see you family doctor as soon as you get home. In the meantime, 
      there is nothing to lose by drinking cranberry juice. Unsweetened 
      cranberry juice makes your urine more acidic, providing a 
      unsupportive environment for bacteria to proliferate. You can also 
      try eliminating caffeine and alcohol, both of which irritate the 
      bladder. If you can't eliminate them during finals, at least try 
      to drink less of them and drink enough water throughout the day to 
      dilute them. Also, many women find that cutting down on refined 
      sugars helps lessen the severity of urinary infections, and 
      prevent them from happening in the first place. These are mostly 
      precautionary measures, you really need to see a clinician as soon 
      as possible to take care of the issue at hand.

<p>
<dd><a href="about.html"><i>Alice</i></a>
<p>
<h4>December 23, 1994</h4>
<p>
</html>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO>WTX020-B05-573</DOCNO>

<font color="#ff3009"><font size=+1><b>
<center><h1><BR>The staff of Citrus Industry is wishing you and yours 
a blessed holiday season, a fruitful new year, and a tangerine 
in the toe of your stocking.</font></h1></center></B>

<br>
<hr width=75%>
<br>
         
         </TD>
</TR>

</B>

<CENTER><TABLE border = 5>
<TR>
<TD BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><font color="#000000"><font size=+1><b>
<center><h1><BR><A NAME="boron">The Consultant's Workshop<br>
Giant hail storm destroys Polk County citrus crops</a></font></h1><br>
By Steven Rogers, Ph.D, Ecostat, Inc. </center></B>




<br><br><hr width=75%>
      
      <p align=Left>

<p align=Center><font size=+2><b>Hail damage is a rare and potentially devastating form<br>
 of citrus crop injury in Florida.</font></b>
<br><br><hr width=75%>
      
      
      
    <center><img src="cihail.jpg">  
      
      <p align=Left>

<img src="cispacer3.gif">  Specific incidents of hail damaging Florida citrus have been
 poorly documented since growers are usually unprepared to acquire and interpret 
 scientific information regarding the amount and type of hail that damages their crops.
   References to hail in the citrus literature are usually limited to a notable 
   photograph and a short paragraph about the uniqueness of the climatology.  
   Hail is not even indexed in any edition of Citrus Growing in Florida.  On many 
   crops (including citrus in Japan), considerable effort has been expended into hail 
   suppression research.  However, most citrus references implicitly agree that little 
   can be done to prevent hail damage due to the cost of management and the constantly 
   changing conditions in Florida hailstorms that preclude forecasters from issuing 
   sufficiently advanced warnings.  An informal survey of growers and weather 
   observers suggested that giant hail events in a given Florida citrus grove occur 
   only once or twice every 100 years; thus, this article serves as the most complete 
   non-technical description of such a rare meteorological event.  Readers wishing 
   more quantitative information about the storm are referred to the companion 
   article on hail crop damage presented in the 1996 Proceedings of the Florida State 
   Horticultural Society. <br>
   
  
  
  <p align=Left>

<font size=+1><b>Features of the storm.</b></font><br>
  <img src="cispacer3.gif">On March 30, 1996, at approximately 2:30 p.m., a severe hailstorm occurred 
  in Polk County that resulted in catastrophic losses to some citrus crops.  
  The storm migrated eastward through Polk County from eastern Hillsborough 
  County traveling through parts of Lakeland, Highland City, Bartow and 
  Lake Wales.  Some hailstones exceeding the size of softballs were reported, 
  but most were 2 to 3 inches in diameter (Fig. 1).  This thunderstorm composed 
  of a tall cumulonimbus cloud with a strong central updraft and circulation 
  vortex met the defined requirements of a "supercell" storm.  Giant hail 
  (i.e. hail greater than 2 to 3 inches in diameter) precipitated over a 
  wide belt of Polk County as the storm traveled eastward.  Thunder, lighting 
  and tornadoes accompanied the storm, and Federal Aviation Administration air 
  traffic controllers reported that the sky turned as "black as ink" immediately 
  prior to some hail events.  Ground temperatures during the storm were 
  approximately 80<SUP><FONT SIZE= "-4">o</FONT SIZE></SUP> F, while temperatures near 50,000 feet approached - 100<SUP><FONT SIZE= "-4">o</FONT SIZE></SUP> F.  
  Updraft and horizontal windspeeds were estimated by the NWS at much greater 
  than 100 mph.
  
  
  
  <br>
  <p align=Left>

<font size=+1><b>Crop Damages.</b></font><br>
  <img src="cispacer3.gif">The NWS did not acquire official estimates 
  of crop damages associated with the storm.  However, several unharvested 
  citrus groves were in the storm trajectory and included red grapefruit and 
  orange varieties targeted for fresh markets.  The hail caused biological 
  losses of approximately 90% with the trees exhibiting extensive leaf loss 
  and 30 to 50% of the crop knocked off the trees.  Leaves were extremely 
  tattered and both leaves and small branches were lobbed to the ground.  
  Some fruits on the ground appeared with undamaged rinds, so strong winds 
  may have contributed to the crop losses.  Sub-terminal bark lesions were 
  also extensive.
  
  
    
  <br>
  <p align=Left>

<font size=+1><b>Damages during the storm.</b></font><br>
  <img src="cispacer3.gif">  Some recently set fruits that were to be harvested 
  the following season were damaged or dislodged, so the hail affected the 
  following seasons crop and tree health.  Of those mature fruits that escaped 
  dislodging by the hail, many showed lesions of completely severed large 
  sections (Fig. 2). On fruits struck to the ground, some were found with 
  approximately 1 inch hail imbedded inside, indicative of a high energy of 
  impact.  Interestingly, lesions often occurred in an "inverted-V" shear.  
  Apparently, hail initially impacted the upper half of exposed fruits.  
  The energy propelled the hail into the fruit, shearing the rind open as 
  it continued to travel on into the flesh, splitting it into the inverted-V 
  laceration.  In oranges, if hail impacted the fruit at a trajectory directed 
  toward the central axis, then it sometimes became imbedded in the flesh.  
  However, if the impact trajectory was directed off-center, the velocity of 
  the hail more likely propelled it on past the fruit, severing that sector of 
  the fruit into which it came into passing contact.  Due perhaps to their 
  thicker rinds, grapefruits appeared more likely to contain imbedded hail, 
  regardless of the impact trajectory of the hail.  In almost all instances, 
  hail lacerations on oranges were more traumatic than on grapefruits subjected 
  to equivalent hail shock.
  
  
    <br>
  <p align=Left>

<font size=+1><b>Damages several weeks after the storm.</b></font><br>
  <img src="cispacer3.gif">  Site investigations several weeks following 
  the hailstorm confirmed as expected that the damages worsened over time.  
  In addition to punctured oil gland injuries, fruit droppage increased as 
  ethylene-activated abscission cell layers continued to dislodge injured 
  fruits.  Fruit flies, insects associated with fruit decay and secondarily 
  pathogenic fungi symptomatically identified as Phytophthora citrophthora, 
  Penicillium spp. and Endomyces geotrichum, invaded remaining damaged fruit 
  tissues, resulting in injuries and infections sufficient to drop fruit which 
  were not dislodged by the physical impact of the hailstones themselves.  
  Similar infections developed on many apparently undamaged fruits on the 
  ground, rendering salvage operations impractical.  It was also 
  increasingly evident that flowering and fruit set were decreased as the 
  crop set appeared lower in the hail-affected trees than in trees not damaged 
  by the giant hail.
  
  
    
  
  
  
  <br>
   <hr width=75%>
      
      
      
      
      <center><img src="ciorange.jpg">
      
      <p align=Left>

<font size=+1><b>Damages six months after the storm.</b></font><br>
<img src="cispacer3.gif">  Six months after the storm, many of the current season's 
fruits manifested injuries that developed from the hail impact occurring the 
previous Spring.  These were fruits that set prior to the Spring storm, 
but were not dislodged by the impacting hail.  These fruit could escape  
the initial dislodging due to their small size and comparatively elastic rind, 
which enabled them to be knocked to the side as the hail came into contact with 
them.  Symptoms appearing on these fruits later in the year consisted primarily of 
"pockmark" lesions on the rind.  Citrus rust mite populations and greasy spot 
disease did not appear dramatically different on the hail affected fruits and 
leaves - at least at the 3 to 6 ft height at which most fruits were sampled.  
Wood rots were found to occur on some of the hail damaged branches, especially 
those in which the terminal points were severed or killed.  However, most 
sub-terminal branch lesions were found to be healing over and the leaves 
and fruits on these branches appeared relatively healthy, although maturing 
slightly earlier than usual.  Many tattered and torn leaves did not exfoliate, 
but were found still to be attached to the trees in the Fall, enabling them to 
continue sourcing photosynthates to the maturing crop.
 <br>


<br><hr width=75%>
      
      <p align=Left>


<font size=+1><b>Damages to next season's crop.</b></font><br>
<img src="cispacer3.gif">  Crop and economic losses from the hail storm 
extended into the following season.  Dead wood was more prevalent in the 
hail-affected groves than in groves that escaped the storm, especially in 
the tops of canopies exposed to the direct impact of the incoming hail.  
In fact, these canopy tops appeared with a preponderance of dead 
branches - thinned and somewhat "ragged".  Consequently, the incidence 
and severity of melanose lesions appeared somewhat greater in the 
hail-affected trees, despite the application of an additional 77% cupric 
hydroxide spray (50% metallic cupric ion) to manage the epidemic.  
This damage/disease profile suggested that severely hail damaged 
trees may benefit from a follow-up hedging/topping/cleaning program 
to help reduce the inoculum potential of melanose disease in subsequent 
seasons.  Standard quality tests indicated that fruits on trees and branches 
stressed by the hail matured slightly earlier than fruit on trees and branches 
not subject to the physical hail stress, rendering first market, high value 
crop harvest operations more difficult to coordinate.  Unfortunately, insurance 
loss estimates did not take into account damages occurring to the following 
season's crop.  Therefore, total economic losses were probably underestimated 
by the percentage of the next season's crop dropped, diseased or not set as a 
result of the previous seasons hail.


<br><br><hr width=75%>
      
      <p align=Left>



<font size=+1><b>Despite their rarity in Florida,</b></font><br>
<img src="cispacer3.gif"> crop damages caused by hailstones in the 
United States historically have been enormous.  Prior to about 1960 
in fact, crop damages comprised about three-quarters of total U.S. hail 
losses.  As American society has evolved from agrarian to urban, however, 
greater hail losses today occur in metropolitan areas.  For example, a 1992 
hail storm in Orlando caused $60 million in damages and was ranked as that 
citys worst natural disaster, exceeding even the damage caused by Hurricane 
Donna in 1960.  Hurricanes, tornadoes, lightning and freezes command more 
dramatic attention, but worldwide - and to a few unfortunate citrus 
growers - hail ranks as one of the most dangerous and destructive of all 
severe weather phenomena.<br>

<br><hr width=75%>
      
      <p align=Left>

 <br>
         
         </TD>
</TR>

<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff" LINK="#ff110a" alink="#989394" TEXT="#000000" BACKGROUND="rwdek.jpg">

<TD BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><font size=+1><font color="#047208"><b>

<center><img src="ciruss1.jpg">

<br>
<hr width=75%>
<br>

<font color="#ff3009"><font size=+1><b>
<center><h1><BR>Hedging and Topping:</font></h1>
<h3>more than horticulture is involved</h3></center></B>

<br>
<hr width=75%>
<br>
         
        </font></B><br> </TD>
</TR>

<br>




<br>

<TR>
<TD BGCOLOR="#ffffff"><font color="#000000"><font size=+1><b>
<center>
By Ernie Neff </center></B>





<hr width=75%>
      
      <p align=Left>

<p align=Center><font size=+2><b>Charlie Russ:</font><br></b>
<font size=+1><b>Citrus By Choice.</font><br></b>


<br><hr width=75%>
      
      
      
    <center><img src="ciruss2.jpg">  
      
      <p align=Left>

<img src="cispacer3.gif">Experts agree there are a handful of important horticultural,
 economic and practical reasons why citrus growers hedge and top their trees. 
 Primary reasons include allowing the proper distribution of sunlight in trees 
 and keeping drive middles open for equipment access.<br>
   
  
  
  <p align=Left>


  <img src="cispacer3.gif">But Charlie Russ knows there are other considerations
   as well - like aesthetics and psychology. He should know. His Orange 
   Service Co., one of Florida's oldest and largest hedgers and toppers, 
   prunes 115-130,000 acres of grove a year.
  
  
  
  <br>
  <p align=Left>


  <img src="cispacer3.gif">"They like the way it (hedging and topping) 
  looks," he said emphatically. He explained that Americans have been 
  taught "to like multiples of things in a uniform arrangement." He said 
  citrus growers like the neat, uniform look that hedging and topping gives 
  their trees. "It is a consideration in every person's decision-making process, 
  whether he'll admit it or not," Russ said.
  
  
    
  <br>
  <p align=Left>


  <img src="cispacer3.gif">Russ said most growers, generally considered 
  among the most practical of people, will look at a newly hedged grove 
  and say, "It looks pretty." A corporate chief executive officer who 
  doesn't know horticulture will visit a newly hedged grove and say the 
  exact same thing - "It looks pretty." 
  
  
    <br>
  <p align=Left>


  <img src="cispacer3.gif">Not that there's anything wrong with a pretty grove! 
  In fact, a proper hedging and topping maintenance program is a good 
  horticultural and economic practice, regardless of the motivation.
  
  
   
   
     <br>
  <p align=Left>


  <img src="cispacer3.gif">Russ added that even though aesthetics is 
  a consideration, it isn't the primary reason most growers hedge and top. 
  He believes that horticultural and economic considerations are the main 
  reasons most growers prune, and properly so. 
  
  
  
  <br>
   
      
      
 
      
      <p align=Left>

<font size=+1><b>HORTICULTURAL REASONS</b></font><br>
<img src="cispacer3.gif">"The biggest reason (to hedge and top) is the entrapment
 of light," Russ said. "Growers hedge to address the foliage surface at various 
 positions in the tree to allow the inception of light."
 <br>


<br>
      
      <p align=Left>



<img src="cispacer3.gif">Every grower knows that sunlight is one of the 
key ingredients in tree growth. Proper hedging and topping allows sunlight
 to get to all parts of a tree's canopy, including the bottom. To let light
  get to the bottom, many growers hedge at an angle up to 10-15 degrees so 
  that the tree's bottom is wider than its top. Russ said a 10-12.5 degree 
  angle is popular in Florida and some growers go as high as 25 degrees. 
  Hedge a tree straight up and down, as was the practice many years ago, and 
  the bottom of the tree's canopy will actually die back from lack of sunlight, 
  Russ said.
  
  
  <br>
      
      <p align=Left>



<img src="cispacer3.gif">He said since hardly any light gets farther 
into a tree than three feet, growers want only two to three feet of 
foliage inside the hedger's cut on a mature tree.


<br>
      
      <p align=Left>



<img src="cispacer3.gif">Russ agrees with a University of Florida Institute 
of Food and Agricultural Sciences (IFAS) general formula regarding the ratio 
between a tree's height and the drive middle. That formula calls for the tree's 
height to be twice the width of the drive middle, measured at the bottom of the 
tree. If there's an eight-foot opening from tree canopy to tree canopy in 
the drive middle, the tree should be 16 feet tall. Russ said the formula is 
a good guide to help ensure that trees get proper doses of sunlight.



<br>
      
      <p align=Left>



<img src="cispacer3.gif">Another key horticultural consideration 
in hedging and topping is maintenance of a tree's proper shoot 
to root (or trunk to root) ratio. If either the root system or 
canopy of a tree is significantly larger than the other, the tree 
will suffer. Topping and hedging can both be used to keep the ratio 
in balance. Many flatwoods growers use topping to maintain that shoot 
to root ratio, since root systems are limited by shallow root zones.


<br>
      
      <p align=Left>



<img src="cispacer3.gif">Some growers hedge and top in an effort to control 
alternate bearing, a situation in which crops are heavy one year and light 
the next. Pruning after a light crop and before an expected heavy crop often 
helps reduce alternate bearing.


<br>
      
      <p align=Left>



<img src="cispacer3.gif">Some growers also hedge and top in an effort to 
rejuvenate groves in which tree canopies are overgrown or the shoot to 
root ratio is out of whack. Russ said in such situations, deep cuts are 
made into heavy wood and spurs juvenile growth.  Over a year or two, he said, 
the tree often recovers to a fully productive status. However, there is some 
controversy within the industry over the value of rejuvenative hedging, which 
makes up less than five percent of Russ' business.



<br>
      
      <p align=Left>



<img src="cispacer3.gif">The vast majority of growers practice annual 
or every-other-year hedging and topping maintenance programs that virtually 
all experts agree are beneficial. Consequently, the recommendations Russ makes
 here are primarily for maintenance programs.


<br><br><hr width=75%>
      
      <p align=Left>



<font size=+1><b>ECONOMIC AND PRACTICAL REASONS</b></font><br>
<img src="cispacer3.gif">Russ said although it's not a widespread practice, 
some fresh fruit growers hedge to control the number of fruit on each tree. 
If they want large size fruit that might bring a better price next season, 
"they actually hedge to reduce the fruit bearing surface so that the fruit 
that's there will gain size." He said some growers of tangerines, Murcottes 
and tangelos hedge to cut off a third of their crop in May or June so the 
remaining fruit will grow larger.<br>


  <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">Many growers use hedging to maintain enough drive 
middle width for sprayers and other grove equipment to pass between rows.<br>

  <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">Hedging and topping both allow more efficient 
spray applications. Topping keeps trees at heights where sprayers are 
effective, and the reduced foliage left by hedging allows better spray 
penetration. Topping also keeps trees at a height where fruit is readily 
accessible for harvesters.<br>


<br><p align=Left>



<font size=+1><b>HOW OFTEN, AND WHEN?</b></font><br>
<img src="cispacer3.gif">Most growers hedge annually to maintain the depth 
of foliage inside the cut at three feet. Depending on growth, however, some 
get by with hedging every other year and topping even less frequently.<br>


  <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">Often, annual or biannual hedging simply cuts off 
8-12 inches of new growth that has appeared since the last hedging.<br>


 <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">One advantage of an annual or biannual maintenance
 hedging and topping program is that the debris is so light it can simply 
 be left on the grove floor. Heavier hedging, such as that done for rejuvenation,
  drops heavy wood on the ground, and it is expensive to dispose of this debris.<br>
  
  
   <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">For all fruit varieties except Valencia oranges, 
most growers hedge after this year's crop is harvested and prior to the 
spring bloom. Russ recommends that growers not hedge later than two or 
three weeks after spring petal fall. "If you go more than three weeks after 
petal fall, you're going to remove (new) fruit you don't want to remove," 
he said. Because most prune after the crop is harvested, the biggest hedging
 and topping months are December through March, but many hedge right up to June.<br>
 
 
   <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">Russ said there are two schools of thought on the 
hedging of Valencias, which carry both a new crop and a soon-to-be-harvested
 crop of fruit through the spring. He said many growers hedge shortly after 
 harvest, or as late as August. However, many others hedge prior to bloom, 
 usually from November to March. "The industry trend is toward pre-bloom. 
 I'm on the fence on this." <br>
 
 
    <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">Experts recommend against doing heavy rejuvenation 
hedging or topping late in the fall or early in the winter because of cold 
considerations. Heavy pruning reduces protective canopy levels and spurs new
 growth that is very susceptible to cold weather. <br>
 
 
     <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">But Russ said there's no problem with maintenance 
hedging and topping in the fall because a relatively small amount of canopy 
is being removed. Maintenance pruning doesn't greatly reduce protective canopy
 or spur much growth. <br>
 
 
      <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">Most growers start hedging when groves are about four 
years old, Russ said. They hedge then because the trees will generally overgrow
 their drive middles after five or six years. <br>
 
 
  <br><hr width=75%>
      
      <p align=Left>



<font size=+1><b>Charlie Russ<br>
citrus by choice</b></font><br>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">Most citrus growers own a wide array of grove 
equipment and they or their employees do everything from mowing to spraying.
 But when it comes to hedging and topping their trees, virtually all go outside
  their own grove or company. <br>
  
  
     <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">"They opt, and I think wisely so, to use me or somebody 
else to do their work," said Charlie Russ, owner of Orange Service Co. 
Russ said hedging and topping requires sophisticated operators and maintenance,
 as well as some engineering expertise, to keep the big pruning machines running
  properly.<br>
  
  
      <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">Although both large and small growers call for outside
 pruning help, larger growers are more likely to know exactly how they want the
  job done. Often, such growers have full-time production managers paid to make 
  such decisions.<br>
  
  
        <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">Smaller, independent growers are more likely to want 
some advice. "We tend to make more recommendations there, and they tend to 
seek our input more," Russ said. He said smaller growers might say, "I want 
to do some trimming. I don't want to overcut it. What width would you recommend?"
Or they might ask his advice on a specific fruit variety they're having hedged and
 topped, like Murcottes and other mandarins. (Since Murcotte trees have been known
  to collapse under the weight of their fruit, some Murcotte owners have those trees
   hedged more drastically to reduce the fruit load. Some other mandarin varieties
    also tend to overcrop, and their owners likewise will use hedging and topping
     to reduce fruit loads.)<br>
     
     
      <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">When growers call on Russ, they're talking to a veteran 
hedger and topper who's also a fellow grower. Like many of his customers, 
he's experienced the ups and downs - including the devastating freezes of 
the 1980s - that go with growing citrus.<br>


   <br><p align=Left>



<font size=+1><b>CITRUS BY CHOICE</b></font><br>
<img src="cispacer3.gif">The 52-year-old Russ didn't come to citrus by birth. 
Although he was raised in Haines City, his only family citrus connection was 
his mother's job as office manager and assistant secretary-treasurer at Waverly
 Citrus Growers Association. "I got influenced by that," he recalled.<br>


  <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">As a teenager, Russ worked at Haines City Citrus Growers
 Association, hoeing groves and moving fruit by hand cart at the packing house. 
 Grower returns were good in those days, and Russ saw citrus growing as a possible
  career choice.<br>
  
  
    <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">After graduating from the University of Florida, 
where he majored in citrus production, Russ served in the military and 
worked as a fertilizer salesman. While still in his mid 20s, he became 
assistant production manager for large grove owner Libby in Lake County. 
He soon became a crop advisor or technical assistant with Libby, and got 
involved in corporate research projects on fertilizer, spray materials, 
herbicides and abscission chemicals. He also ventured into citrus growing 
by buying a five-acre grove in 1968. He would continue to add to his grove 
holdings over the next several years.<br>


 <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">Russ went to work with Citrus Systems in 1972-73, 
promoting mechanical harvesting in an effort to create a market for the 
company's abscission chemicals. Neither mechanical harvesting nor the 
abscission chemicals that might make it feasible caught on at that time.<br>


<br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">In his late 20s in 1969, Russ started a sideline citrus
 business removing blighted trees with front-end loaders. (At that time, he 
 recalled, blight was called sand hill decline.) In 1973 he added hedging to 
 his part-time business, and he went into hedging full time in February 1974. 
 Several years before, he had incorporated his business as Orange Service Co.<br>
 
 
 <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">Citrus production boomed in the northern edge of 
the citrus belt in the 1970s and Russ had eight hedgers and two toppers - all
 built in his Clermont shop ?by the early 1980s. Most of his hedging and 
 topping customers were in Lake, Orange and Polk counties.<br>
 
 
 <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">When the December 1983 freeze walloped groves in 
those three counties, it also walloped Russ. "1983 was a real setback," 
he recalled. After the January 1985 freeze just 13 months later, "we'd 
lost 87-89 percent of our customers in the north area."<br>


 <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">In 1986, Russ opened an Orange Service Co. shop in Fort
 Pierce to provide hedging and topping for the expanding southern citrus belt. 
 He opened another shop in Arcadia in 1988. His expansion to the south may have 
 saved his company. By the time the Christmas 1989 freeze was over, 97 percent 
 of his northern citrus belt customers had succumbed to the killer freezes of 
 the 1980s. During most of the 1980s and the early 1990s, Orange Service Co. 
 worked at only 50-60 percent of its capacity. "It was very difficult for us."<br>
 
 
 <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">The 1980s were also difficult to Russ, the grower. 
He had accumulated 300 acres of orange groves by 1981, and the 1980s 
freezes chipped away at his groves. The 1989 freeze killed all of his 
trees. He replanted 50 acres in Clermont in 1991, leaving him with 
one-sixth the citrus acreage he once owned.<br>


 <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">Orange Service's original Clermont shop now serves 
primarily as the company's manufacturing and engineering shop. Most of the 
hedging and topping services are provided out of the Arcadia and Fort Pierce 
facilities.<br>


 <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">Orange Service builds its own hedgers and toppers in
 the Clermont shop. Over the years, the shop has also built  sprayers, 
 1,000-gallon water supply trucks for spraying operations and furrow 
 shapers and vee mowers for bedded groves. It still sells the furrow shapers
  and mowers to growers.<br>
  
  
  <br><p align=Left>




<img src="cispacer3.gif">Today, Orange Service Co. has seven hedgers, four toppers 
and a skirter that it uses to prune groves all over the citrus belt. Russ said 
the company spends about $25,000 a year on in-house research that might improve 
hedging and topping procedures. Like the citrus business, Russ said, the research 
efforts have had varying results. "Some pay off and some don't."<br>


<br><hr width=75%>
      
      <p align=Left>

 <br>
         
         </TD>
</TR>





</font></B>
<br></TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>

<P>
<H2>Susan G. Komen Breast Cancer Foundation</H2>
<P>
<H4>Support Document</H4></TR>
</TABLE>
<BR>

<P><HR WIDTH = 100% ALIGN=CENTER SIZE=2><BR>

<H2><B>a. Risk Factors</B></H2>
<P><HR WIDTH = 100% ALIGN=CENTER SIZE=2><BR>

<P>
<H4><U><B>Risk Factors</U></B></H4>
<P>
<P><U><B>Key Risk Factors:</U></B><BR>

<P><B>	The most proven and significant risk factors are being female and getting older.</B>  <U>75% of the women with breast cancer have no known risk factors.</U>			<BR>

<P>	*	A <B>personal history</B> of breast, ovarian, or endometrial cancer can also increase a woman's risk of developing breast cancer.<BR>

<P>	*	A <B>family history</B> of breast, colon, ovarian, or endometrial cancer may prove to be a risk factor for some women.  <U>Only 5-10% of breast cancers are due to what one inherits (family history).</U><BR>

<P><U><B>Other Considerations:</U></B><BR>

<P>	<B>Radiation exposure</B><BR>
<B>	</B>Mammograms, dental or chest x-rays have not been proven to be risk factors for breast cancer.  Improved equipment and film have minimized x-ray exposure.  American College of Radiology (ACR) accreditation requires there be no more than 1 rad of radiation exposure per breast per mammogram.  During a year's time one receives more natural radiation exposure from the environment than from a mammogram.<BR>

<P><B>	Age at Menarche (when period begins) and Menopause</B><BR>
	There seems to be a slight increase in risk if a woman begins her period early (before age 12) and/or has a late onset of menopause (after age 55).  The risk appears to be related to the number of years a woman is exposed to monthly hormonal changes.  However, this factor is only a very slight increase.<BR>

<P><B>	Age at First Pregnancy/Having no children</B><BR>
	There does seem to be a correlation between the age of a woman at her first pregnancy and the risk of developing breast cancer.  The younger a woman is at the time of her first pregnancy (age 20 or younger), the lower the risk of breast cancer.  Also, there is a slight increased risk for women who do not have children.  Again, this is a small factor in determining an individuals overall risk.<BR>

<P><B>	Mild to Moderate Alcohol Consumption</B><BR>
	Studies have consistently found that moderate alcohol consumption (3 or more drinks/week) increase a womans risk of developing breast cancer.  More data needs to be collected on this issue.<BR>

<P><B>	Oral Contraceptives</B><BR>
	Studies indicate that oral contraceptives do not increase the risk of breast cancer in women over 45 years of age.  More recent studies have shown an increase in breast cancer risk for women under 45 who take birth control pills.  Further studies are needed to help clarify the relationship between oral contraceptives and breast cancer risk.<BR>

<P><B>	Replacement Hormones</B><BR>
	There have been conflicting studies on linking hormone replacement therapy and an increased risk in breast cancer.  At this time, there is <U>not</U> a link that suggests that HRT <I>causes</I> breast cancer. However, some tumors are sensitive to hormones, and the hormones stimulate their growth. In these cases, the hormones would cause the tumors to grow faster.  <BR>

<P>	Hormone replacement therapy has been proven to reduce the risk of cardiovascular disease and osteoporosis. The Susan G. Komen Breast Cancer Foundation recommends each woman thoroughly discuss the question of hormone replacement therapy with her doctor.<BR>

<P><B>	Smoking</B><BR>
	No clear association between cigarette smoking and breast cancer risk has been established.<BR>

<P><B>	Abortion</B><BR>
	There have been several studies on both sides of this issue, but there is no conclusive evidence to link abortion, either natural or induced, with an increased risk of breast cancer.<BR>

<P>	<B>Diet  </B><BR>
<B>	</B>Although research on heart disease and colon cancer has shown dietary associations, current research linking breast cancer and diet is not conclusive.  Initial findings do suggest an association between breast cancer risk and a high fat, low fiber diet, however additional studies need to be done to further substantiate these findings.<BR>

<P>
<P><A HREF="manual.htm"><B>Document Index</B></A><BR>

<HEAD><TITLE>Merit Badges Beginning With W</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<CENTER><H1>Boy Scout Merit Badge Requirements</H1></CENTER>

The following information is from the Scouts-L list server. If you're in
Scouting and on the Internet, you should belong to Scouts-L.

<P><HR>

<P><A NAME="water"></A>
<CENTER><H3><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/~optimist/art/2695.gif" ALT="[BADGE]">
WATERSKIING</H3></CENTER>

<OL><LI><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/~optimist/art/update95.gif" ALT="[UPDATED in
1995]"> Show that you know first aid for injuries or illnesses that could
occur while waterskiing, including hypothermia, heatstroke, heat exhaustion,
dehydration, sunburn, insect stings, tick bites, blisters, and
hyperventilation.
<LI><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/~optimist/art/update95.gif" ALT="[UPDATED in 1995]">
Do the following:
  <OL TYPE=a><LI><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/~optimist/art/update95.gif"
  ALT="[UPDATED in 1995]"> Identify the conditions that must exist before
  performing CPR on a person. Explain how such conditions are recognized.
  <LI><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/~optimist/art/update95.gif" ALT="[UPDATED in 1995]">
  Demonstrate proper technique for performing CPR on an adult mannequin for
  AT LEAST three minutes.</OL>
<LI><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/~optimist/art/update95.gif" ALT="[UPDATED in 1995]">
Before doing the following requirements, successfully complete the BSA
swimmer test. Jump feetfirst into water over your head in depth, swim 75
yards or 75 meters in a strong manner using one or more of the following
strokes: sidestroke, breaststroke, trudgen, or crawl; then swim 25 yards or
25 meters using an easy resting backstroke. The 100 yards or 100 meters must
be swum continuously and include at least one sharp turn. After completing
the swim, rest by floating as motionless as possible.
<LI>Know the Water-Skier's Safety Code. Promise that you will live up to it.
Follow it in all water work for this badge. Know the safety precautions that
must be used by the boat operator in pulling skiers.
<LI>Show the following water-skier signals to safety observer in boat:
in-gear, start, faster, slower, speed required, speed OK, turns, stop, back
to dock, cut motor, skier in water. Help others to ski by acting as the
safety observer in the boat.
<LI>Show you can adjust binders that fit, to fit. Put on skis in knee-deep
water.
<LI>Make a shallow-water start on two skis without help.
<LI>Show you can fall properly in avoiding an obstacle. Drop handle and coast
to a stop without loss of balance.
<LI>Show you can recover skis that have come off during a fall. Put skis on
in deep water. Make a deep-water start on two skis without help.
<LI>Show you can cross both wakes and return to center of wake without
falling. Repeat three times.
<LI>On two skis, jump off the wake. Lift both skis clear of the water.
<LI>During a demonstration run, lift one ski clear of the water for 2
seconds. Then do the same with the other ski. Show that you are steady and
comfortable on skis at all times.
<LI>Ski on one ski for 30 seconds. Show reasonable control.</OL>

<P><HR>

<P><A NAME="weath"></A>
<CENTER><H3><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/~optimist/art/2700.gif" ALT="[BADGE]">
WEATHER</H3></CENTER>

<OL><LI>Define meteorology. Explain how the weather affects farmers, sailors,
aviators, and the outdoors construction industry. Tell why weather forecasts
are important to each of these groups.
<LI>Name five dangerous weather-related conditions. Give the safety rules for
each when outdoors and explain the difference between a severe weather watch
and a warning. Discuss the safety rules with your family.
<LI>Draw cross sections of a cold front and a warm front showing the location
and movements of the cold and warm air, the frontal slope, the location and
types of clouds associated with the front, and the location of rain. Tell the
differences between a cold front and a warm front.
<LI>Tell what causes wind, why it rains, and how lightning and hail are
formed. Explain the difference between high and low pressure systems in the
atmosphere and tell which is related to good and poor weather.
<LI>Identify and describe clouds in the low, middle, and upper levels of the
atmosphere. Relate these to specific types of weather.
<LI>Draw a diagram of the water cycle and label its major processes. Explain
the water cycle to your counselor.
<LI>Define acid rain. Identify which human activities pollute the atmosphere
as well as the effects such pollution can have on people.
<LI>Do ONE of the following:
  <OL TYPE=a><LI>Make one of the following instruments: wind vane,
  anemometer, rain gauge, hygrometer. Keep a daily weather log for 1 week
  using information from this instrument as well as from other sources such
  as local radio and television stations or NOAA Weather Radio. The following
  information should be recorded at the same time every day: wind direction
  and speed, temperature, precipitation, and types of clouds. Be sure to make
  a note of any morning dew or frost. In the log, also list the weather
  forecasts from radio or television at the same time each day and show how
  the weather turned out.
  <LI>Visit a National Weather Service office or talk with a local radio or
  television weathercaster, private meteorologist, local agricultural
  Extension service office, or university meteorology instructor.  Find out
  what type of weather is most dangerous or damaging to your community.
  Determine how severe weather and flood warnings reach the homes in your
  community.</OL>
<LI>Do ONE of the following:
  <OL TYPE=a><LI>Give a talk of more than 5 minutes to your unit explaining
  the camping safety rules in the event of lightning, flash floods, and
  tornadoes. Before your talk, show your outline to your counselor for
  approval.
  <LI>Read several articles about acid rain and give a prepared talk of more
  than 5 minutes about the articles to your unit. Before your talk, show your
  outline to your counselor for approval.</OL></OL>

<P><HR>

<P><A NAME="white"></A>
<CENTER><H3><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/~optimist/art/2705.gif" ALT="[BADGE]">
WHITEWATER</H3></CENTER>

<OL><LI><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/~optimist/art/update95.gif" ALT="[UPDATED in
1995]"> Show that you know first aid for injuries or illnesses that could
occur while working on the Whitewater merit badge, including hypothermia,
heatstroke, heat exhaustion, dehydration, sunburn, insect stings, tick bites,
blisters, and hyperventilation.
<LI><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/~optimist/art/update95.gif" ALT="[UPDATED in 1995]">
Do the following:
  <OL TYPE=a><LI><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/~optimist/art/update95.gif"
  ALT="[UPDATED in 1995]"> Identify the conditions that must exist before
  performing CPR on a person. Explain how such conditions are recognized.
  <LI><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/~optimist/art/update95.gif" ALT="[UPDATED in 1995]">
  Demonstrate proper technique for performing CPR on an adult mannequin for
  AT LEAST three minutes.</OL>
<LI><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/~optimist/art/update95.gif" ALT="[UPDATED in 1995]">
Before doing the following requirements earn the Canoeing merit badge, then
do the following:
  <OL TYPE=a><LI>Demonstrate basic canoe-handling skills by completing the
  Scout Gate Test within 120 seconds while paddling tandem with a buddy.
  <LI>Review and compare BSA Safety Afloat and the American Whitewater
  Affiliation Safety Code and demonstrate your understanding of these
  principles by answering questions from your counselor.</OL>
<LI>Identify and explain the use of safety equipment on running water.
<LI>Explain the International Scale of River Difficulty and apply the scale
to the stretch of river where you are practicing and demonstrating your
whitewater skills.  Identify the specific characteristics of the river that
are factors in your classification according to the International Scale.
<LI>Explain how to scout and read a river both while afloat and from ashore.
Explain open and closed V's, shoals with broken or dancing water, boils,
strainers, broken drops, haystacks, dams, falls and lowhead obstructions,
eddies, whirlpools, crosscurrents, flat rocks, standing waves, sheer drops,
and heavy water. Demonstrate your ability to read the river where you are
practicing and demonstrating your whitewater skills.
<LI>Explain the differences between flatwater and whitewater canoes; identify
the advantages and special uses for kayaks and decked canoes in running
water. Identify the different materials used in modern whitewater canoe
construction and the advantages and disadvantages of each.
<LI>Identify paddles designed for whitewater use and explain their special
characteristics.
<LI>Do ONE of the following:
  <OL TYPE=a><LI>Demonstrate paddle strokes in the bow position of an open
  canoe on running water, for forward movement, sideways movement, and
  backward 4. Repeat in the stern position.
  <LI>Demonstrate forward, backward, and sideways movements on running water
  using a single- or double-bladed paddle in a kayak or decked canoe.</OL>
<LI>While paddling aloud or with a partner in an open canoe, or while alone
in a kayak, demonstrate forward and back ferry, eddy turn, peeling out of an
eddy, and high and low braces.
<LI>Explain and demonstrate:
  <OL TYPE=a><LI>Self-rescue and procedures when capsized in running water.
  <LI>Safe rescue of others in various whitewater situations.
  <LI>Portaging -- when and how to do it.
  <LI>The whitewater buddy system using at least three persons and three
  craft.</OL>
<LI>Discuss the use of inflatable boats on moving water. Explain how to
safely outfit and use an inflatable boat in whitewater including the type of
craft suited to certain water conditions, how to maneuver the craft on the
water, and what special safety precautions should be taken when using an
inflatable boat.
<LI>Explain the risks of "tubing" on moving water.
<LI>Participate in a 1-day whitewater trip for beginners. Help to prepare a
written plan specifying route, schedule, equipment, safety precautions, and
emergency procedures. Determine local rules and obtain permission from local
property owners. Explain what steps you have taken to comply with the BSA
Safety Afloat and the American Whitewater Affiliation Safety Code. Execute
the plan with others.</OL>

<P><HR>

<P><A NAME="wisur"></A>
<CENTER><H3><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/~optimist/art/2710.gif" ALT="[BADGE]">
WILDERNESS SURVIVAL</H3></CENTER>

<OL><LI>From memory, describe the priorities for survival in a backcountry or
wilderness location.
<LI>Describe ways to
  <OL TYPE=a><LI>avoid panic and
  <LI>Maintain a high level of morale when lost.</OL>
<LI>Show that you know firsthand aid for injuries or accidents likely to
occur in backcountry outings, including hypothermia, hyperthermia, heat
stroke, heat exhaustion, frostbite, dehydration, sunburn, stings, ticks,
snakebite, blisters, and hyperventilation.
<LI>Tell what you would do to survive in the:
  <OL TYPE=a><LI>Cold and snowy
  <LI>Wet (forest)
  <LI>Hot and dry (desert)
  <LI>Windy (mountains or plains)
  <LI>Water (ocean or lake)</OL>
<LI>Make up a small survival kit an be able to explain how each item in it is
useful.
<LI>Show that you can start fires using three methods other than matches.
<LI>Do the following:
  <OL TYPE=a><LI>Tell five different ways of attracting attention when lost.
  <LI>Show how to use a signal mirror to attract attention when lost.
  <LI>From memory, describe five international ground-to-air signals and tell
  what they mean.</OL>
<LI>Show that you can find and improvise a natural shelter minimizing the
damage to the environment.
<LI>Spend a night in your shelter.
<LI>Explain how to protect yourself against insects, reptiles, rodents, and
bears.
<LI>Show three ways to purify water.
<LI>Show that you know the proper clothing to be worn in your area on an
overnight in extremely hot weather and extremely cold weather.
<LI>Explain why it usually is not wise to eat edible wild plants or wildlife
in a wilderness survival situation.</OL>

<P><HR>

<P><A NAME="wocar"></A>
<CENTER><H3><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/~optimist/art/2715.gif" ALT="[BADGE]">
WOOD CARVING</H3></CENTER>

<OL><LI>Give the qualities of Wood that are useful for carving. Tell why you
chose the wood used in requirements 4 and 5.
<LI>Do the following:
  <OL TYPE=a><LI>Describe five wood-carving tools. Tell their use.
  <LI>Describe several kinds of sharpening stones. Tell how they are used.
  <LI>Show how to sharpen a pocket-knife and other tools used in wood
  carving. Use a sharpening stone and a "slipstick" that you have made.</OL>
<LI>Show the safety principles for using a pocketknife and woodcarving tools.
<LI>Plan and carve in the round a simple object. Prepare it for finish.
<LI>Plan and carve in low relief a design on some simple project. Prepare it
for finish.</OL>

<P><HR>

<P><A NAME="woodw"></A>
<CENTER><H3><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/~optimist/art/2720.gif" ALT="[BADGE]">
WOODWORK</H3></CENTER>

<OL><LI>Do the following:
  <OL TYPE=a><LI>Describe how timber is grown, harvested, and milled. Tell
  how lumber us cured, seasoned, graded, and sized.
  <LI>Collect and label blocks of six kinds of wood useful in woodworking.
  Describe the chief qualities of each. Give the best uses of each.</OL>
<LI>Do the following:
  <OL TYPE=a><LI>Show proper care and use of all working tools and which you
  own or use at home or school.
  <LI>Sharpen correctly the cutting edges of two tools.</OL>
<LI>Make something useful of wood. Use a saw, plane, hammer, and brace and
bit to make it. Cut parts from lumber which you have measured and squared
from working drawings.
<LI>Do the following:
  <OL TYPE=a><LI>Make a working of a carpentry project. List the material
  needed.
  <LI>Take it. Report on the time spent and cost of things used.</OL>
<LI>Do any TWO of the following:
  <OL TYPE=a><LI>Make working drawings of a project needing
    <OL TYPE=1><LI>Beveled or rounded edges or curved or incised cuttings.
    <LI>Miter, dowel, or mortise and tenon joints. Make it.</OL>
  <LI>Make something for which you have to turn duplicate parts on a lathe.
  <LI>Make a cabinet, box or something else with a door or lid fastened with
  inset hinges.
  <LI>Help make a repair wooden toys for needy children; or help carry out a
  carpentry service project.
  <LI>Make a scale  model of a house or barn.</OL>
<LI>Talk with a cabinetmaker or carpenter. Find out job opportunities and
conditions, needed training, apprenticeship, work hours, pay rates, and union
organization for woodworking craftsmen where you live.</OL>

<P><HR>

<CENTER>
<IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/~optimist/art/update94.gif" ALT="[UPDATED in 1994]">
<IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/~optimist/art/update95.gif" ALT="[UPDATED in 1995]">
<IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/~optimist/art/update96.gif" ALT="[UPDATED in 1996]">
<BR>Revisions are highlighted with the above symbols
<BR>and are effective September 1st of the year noted.</CENTER>

<HTML>

<!--Web Page by Michael Kauffmann, Copyright(C) 1996-->

<HEAD><TITLE>Merit Badges -- Weather</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffff">

<CENTER><H1>Boy Scout Merit Badge Requirements</H1></CENTER>

The following information is from the Scouts-L list server. If you're in
Scouting and on the Internet, you should belong to Scouts-L.

<P><HR>

<P><A NAME="weath"></A>
<CENTER><H3><IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/~optimist/art/2700.gif" ALT="[BADGE]">
WEATHER</H3></CENTER>

<OL><LI>Define meteorology. Explain how the weather affects farmers, sailors,
aviators, and the outdoors construction industry. Tell why weather forecasts
are important to each of these groups.
<LI>Name five dangerous weather-related conditions. Give the safety rules for
each when outdoors and explain the difference between a severe weather watch
and a warning. Discuss the safety rules with your family.
<LI>Draw cross sections of a cold front and a warm front showing the location
and movements of the cold and warm air, the frontal slope, the location and
types of clouds associated with the front, and the location of rain. Tell the
differences between a cold front and a warm front.
<LI>Tell what causes wind, why it rains, and how lightning and hail are
formed. Explain the difference between high and low pressure systems in the
atmosphere and tell which is related to good and poor weather.
<LI>Identify and describe clouds in the low, middle, and upper levels of the
atmosphere. Relate these to specific types of weather.
<LI>Draw a diagram of the water cycle and label its major processes. Explain
the water cycle to your counselor.
<LI>Define acid rain. Identify which human activities pollute the atmosphere
as well as the effects such pollution can have on people.
<LI>Do ONE of the following:
  <OL TYPE=a><LI>Make one of the following instruments: wind vane,
  anemometer, rain gauge, hygrometer. Keep a daily weather log for 1 week
  using information from this instrument as well as from other sources such
  as local radio and television stations or NOAA Weather Radio. The following
  information should be recorded at the same time every day: wind direction
  and speed, temperature, precipitation, and types of clouds. Be sure to make
  a note of any morning dew or frost. In the log, also list the weather
  forecasts from radio or television at the same time each day and show how
  the weather turned out.
  <LI>Visit a National Weather Service office or talk with a local radio or
  television weathercaster, private meteorologist, local agricultural
  Extension service office, or university meteorology instructor.  Find out
  what type of weather is most dangerous or damaging to your community.
  Determine how severe weather and flood warnings reach the homes in your
  community.</OL>
<LI>Do ONE of the following:
  <OL TYPE=a><LI>Give a talk of more than 5 minutes to your unit explaining
  the camping safety rules in the event of lightning, flash floods, and
  tornadoes. Before your talk, show your outline to your counselor for
  approval.
  <LI>Read several articles about acid rain and give a prepared talk of more
  than 5 minutes about the articles to your unit. Before your talk, show your
  outline to your counselor for approval.</OL></OL>

<P><HR>

<IMG BORDER=0 SRC="/~optimist/art/update96.gif" ALT="[UPDATED in 1996]">
<BR>Revisions are highlighted with the above symbols
<BR>and are effective September 1st of the year noted.</CENTER>

<title>

Debby's Debut

</title>

</head>

<body bgcolor=ffffff>





<p>

<a name="top">	<!--REFERENCE POINT; TOP OF PAGE-->

<center>





			<!--HEADER GRAPHIC-->

		<a href="../../../images/headau.map">

<img src="../../../images/headau.gif" ISMAP width=480 height=100 border=0 alt="Atlantic Unbound">

</a>





</center>





<p>



<font size=4>August 1863</font><p>



<p><!--TITLE-->



<h1>



<center>





DEBBY'S DEBUT</center></h1> <p>



<p>



 <p><center><font size=4>by Louisa May Alcott</font></center>

<p><img src="../../../images/transp.gif" alt="" vspace=10><p>



<p>



<blockquote>



<p>



<p><br><p><br>



<font size=5>O</font><font size=3>n a cheery June day Mrs. Penelope Carroll and her niece Debby Wilder were

whizzing along on their way to a certain gay watering-place, both in the best

of humors with each other and all the world beside. Aunt Pen was concocting

sundry mild romances, and laying harmless plots for the pursuance of her

favorite pastime, match-making; for she had invited her pretty relative to join

her summer jaunt, ostensibly that the girl might see a little of fashionable

life, but the good lady secretly proposed to herself to take her to the beach

and get her a rich husband, very much as she would have proposed to take her to

Broadway and get her a new bonnet, for both articles she considered necessary,

but somewhat difficult for a poor girl to obtain.<p>



<p>



<p>



Debby was slowly getting her poise, after the excitement of a first visit to

New York; for ten days of bustle had introduced the young philosopher to a new

existence, and the working-day world seemed to have vanished when she made her

last pat of butter in the dairy at home. For an hour she sat thinking over the

good-fortune which had befallen her, and the comforts of this life which she

had suddenly acquired. Debby was a true girl,--with all a girl's love of ease

and pleasure; and it must not be set down against her that she surveyed her

pretty travelling-suit with much complacency, rejoicing inwardly that she could

use her hands without exposing fractured gloves, that her bonnet was of the

newest mode, needing no veil to hide a faded ribbon or a last year's shape,

that her dress swept the ground with fashionable untidiness, and her boots were

guiltless of a patch,--that she was the possessor of a mine of wealth in two of

the eight trunks belonging to her aunt, that she was travelling like any lady

of the land with man-and maid-servant at her command, and that she was leaving

work and care behind her for a month or two of novelty and rest.<p>



<p>



<p>



When these agreeable facts were fully realized, and Aunt Pen had fallen asleep

behind her veil, Debby took out a book, and indulged in her favorite luxury,

soon forgetting past, present, and future in the inimitable history of Martin

Chuzzlewit. The sun blazed, the cars rattled, children cried, ladies nodded,

gentlemen longed for the solace of prohibited cigars, and newspapers were

converted into sun-shades, nightcaps, and fans; but Debby read on, unconscious

of all about her, even of the pair of eyes that watched her from the opposite

corner of the car. A gentleman with a frank, strong-featured face sat therein,

and amused himself by scanning with thoughtful gaze the countenances of his

fellow-travellers. Stout Aunt Pen, dignified even in her sleep, was a "model of

deportment" to the rising generation; but the student of human nature found a

more attractive subject in her companion, the girl with an apple-blossom face

and merry brown eyes, who sat smiling into her book, never heeding that her

bonnet was awry, and the wind taking unwarrantable liberties with her ribbons

and her hair.<p>



<p>



<p>



Innocent Debby turned her pages, unaware that her fate sat opposite in the

likeness of a serious, black-bearded gentleman, who watched the smiles rippling

from her lips to her eyes with an interest that deepened as the minutes passed.

If his paper had been full of anything but "Bronchial Troches" and "Spalding's

Prepared Glue," he would have found more profitable employment; but it wasn't,

and with the usual readiness of idle souls he fell into evil ways, and

permitted curiosity, that feminine sin, to enter in and take possession of his

manly mind. A great desire seized him to discover what book so interested his

pretty neighbor; but a cover hid the name, and he was too distant to catch it

on the fluttering leaves. Presently a stout Emerald-Islander, with her wardrobe

oozing out of sundry paper parcels, vacated the seat behind the two ladies; and

it was soon quietly occupied by the individual for whom Satan was finding such

indecorous employment. Peeping round the little gray bonnet, past a brown braid

and a fresh cheek, the young man's eye fell upon the words the girl was

reading, and forgot to look away again. Books were the desire of his life; but

an honorable purpose and an indomitable will kept him steady at his ledgers

till he could feel that he had earned the right to read. Like wine to many

another was an open page to him; he read a line, and, longing for more, took a

hasty sip from his neighbor's cup, forgetting that it was a stranger's also.<p>



<p>



<p>



Down the page went the two pairs of eyes, and the merriment from Debby's seemed

to light up the sombre ones behind her with a sudden shine that softened the

whole face and made it very winning. No wonder they twinkled, for Elijah Pogram

spoke, and "Mrs. Hominy, the mother of the modern Gracchi, in the classical

blue cap and the red cotton picket-handkerchief, came down the room in a

procession of one." A low laugh startled Debby, though it was smothered like

the babes in the Tower; and, turning, she beheld the trespasser scarlet with

confusion, and sobered with a tardy sense of his transgression. Debby was not a

starched young lady of the "prune and prism" school, but a frank, free-hearted

little body, quick to read the sincerity of others, and to take looks and words

at their real value. Dickens was her idol; and for his sake she could have

forgiven a greater offense than this. The stranger's contrite countenance and

respectful apology won her good-will at once; and with a finer courtesy than

any Aunt Pen would have taught, she smilingly bowed her pardon, and taking

another book from her basket, opened it, saying, pleasantly,--<p>



<p>



<p>



"Here is the first volume, if you like it, Sir. I can recommend it as an

invaluable consolation for the discomforts of a summer day's journey, and it is

heartily at your service."<p>



<p>



<p>



As much surprised as gratified, the gentleman accepted the book, and retired

behind it with the sudden discovery that wrong-doing has its compensation in

the pleasurable sensation of being forgiven. Stolen delights are well known to

be specially saccharine; and much as this pardoned sinner loved books, it

seemed to him that the interest of the story flagged, and that the enjoyment of

reading was much enhanced by the proximity of a gray bonnet and a girlish

profile. But Dickens soon proved more powerful than Debby, and she was

forgotten, till, pausing to turn a leaf, the young man met her shy glance, as

she asked, with the pleased expression of a child who has shared an apple with

a playmate,--<p>



<p>



<p>



"Is it good?"<p>



<p>



"Oh, very!"--and the man looked as honestly grateful for the book as the boy

would have done for the apple.<p>



<p>



<p>



Only five words in the conversation, but Aunt Pen woke, as if the watchful

spirit of propriety had roused her to pluck her charge from the precipice on

which she stood.<p>



<p>



<p>



"Dora, I'm astonished at you! Speaking to strangers in that free manner is a

most unladylike thing. How came you to forget what I have told you over and

over again about a proper reserve?"<p>



<p>



<p>



The energetic whisper reached the gentleman's ear, and he expected to be

annihilated with a look when his offense was revealed; but he was spared that

ordeal, for the young voice answered, softly,--<p>



<p>



<p>



"Don't faint, Aunt Pen; I only did as I'd be done by; for I had two books, and

the poor man looked so hungry for something to read that I couldn't resist

sharing my 'goodies.' He will see that I'm a countrified little thing in spite

of my fine feathers, and won't be shocked at my want of rigidity and frigidity;

so don't look dismal, and I'll be prim and proper all the rest of the way,--if

I don't forget it."<p>



<p>



<p>



"I wonder who he is; may belong to some of our first families, and in that case

it might be worth while to exert ourselves, you know. Did you learn his name,

Dora?" whispered the elder lady.<p>



<p>



<p>



Debby shook her head, and murmured, "Hush!"--but Aunt Pen had heard of matches

being made in cars as well as in heaven; and as an experienced general, it

became her to reconnoitre, when one of the enemy approached her camp. Slightly

altering her position, she darted an all-comprehensive glance at the invader,

who seemed entirely absorbed, for not an eyelash stirred during the scrutiny.

It lasted but an instant, yet in that instant he was weighed and found wanting;

for that experienced eye detected that his cravat was two inches wider than

fashion ordained, that his coat was not of the latest style, that his gloves

were mended, and his handkerchief neither cambric nor silk. That was enough,

and sentence was passed forthwith,--"Some respectable clerk, good-looking, but

poor, and not at all the thing for Dora"; and Aunt Pen turned to adjust a

voluminous green veil over her niece's bonnet, "To shield it from the dust,

dear," which process also shielded the face within from the eye of man.<p>



<p>



<p>



A curious smile, half mirthful, half melancholy, passed over their neighbor's

lips; but his peace of mind seemed undisturbed, and he remained buried in his

book till they reached --------, at dusk. As he returned it, he offered his

services in procuring a carriage or attending to luggage; but Mrs. Carroll,

with much dignity of aspect, informed him that her servants would attend to

those matters, and, bowing gravely, he vanished into the night.<p>



<p>



<p>



As they rolled away to the hotel, Debby was wild to run down to the beach

whence came the solemn music of the sea, making the twilight beautiful. But

Aunt Pen was too tired to do anything but sup in her own apartment and go early

to bed; and Debby might as soon have proposed to walk up the Great Pyramid as

to make her first appearance without that sage matron to mount guard over her;

so she resigned herself to pie and patience, and fell asleep, wishing it were

to-morrow.<p>



<p>



<p>



At five, A.M., a nightcapped head appeared at one of the myriad windows of the

------- Hotel, and remained there as if fascinated by the miracle of sunrise

over the sea. Under her simplicity of character and girlish merriment Debby

possessed a devout spirit and a nature full of the real poetry of life, two

gifts that gave her dawning womanhood its sweetest charm, and made her what she

was. As she looked out that summer dawn upon the royal marriage of the ocean

and the sun, all petty hopes and longings faded out of sight, and her young

face grew luminous with thoughts too deep for words. Her day was happier for

that silent hour, her life richer for the aspirations that uplifted her like

beautiful strong angels, and left a blessing when they went. The smile of the

June sky touched her lips, the morning red seemed to linger on her cheek, and

in her eye arose a light kindled by the shimmer of that broad sea of gold; for

Nature rewarded her young votary well, and gave her beauty, when she offered

love. How long she leaned there Debby did not know; steps from below roused her

from her reverie, and led her back into the world again. Smiling at herself,

she stole to bed, and lay wrapped in waking dreams as changeful as the shadows

dancing on her chamber-wall.<p>



<p>



<p>



The advent of her aunt's maid, Victorine, some two hours later, was the signal

to be "up and doing"; and she meekly resigned herself into the hands of that

functionary, who appeared to regard her in the light of an animated

pin-cushion, as she performed the toilet-ceremonies with an absorbed aspect,

which impressed her subject with a sense of the solemnity of the occasion.<p>



<p>



<p>



"Now, Mademoiselle, regard yourself, and pronounce that you are ravishing,"

Victorine said at length, folding her hands with a sigh of satisfaction, as she

fell back in an attitude of serene triumph. <p>



<p>



<p>



Debby obeyed, and inspected herself with great interest and some astonishment;

for there was a sweeping amplitude of array about the young lady whom she

beheld in the much-befrilled gown and embroidered skirts, which somewhat

alarmed her as to the navigation of a vessel "with such a spread of sail,"

while a curious sensation of being somebody else pervaded her from the crown of

her head, with its shining coils of hair, to the soles of the French slippers,

whose energies seemed to have been devoted to the production of marvellous

rosettes.<p>



<p>



<p>



"Yes, I look very nice, thank you; and yet I fell like a doll, helpless and

fine, and fancy I was more of a woman in my fresh gingham, with a knot of

clovers in my hair, than I am now. Aunt Pen was very kind to get me all these

pretty things; but I'm afraid my mother would look horrified to see me in such

a high state of flounce externally and so little room to breathe internally."<p>



<p>



<p>



"Your mamma would not flatter me, Mademoiselle; but come now to Madame; she is

waiting to behold you, and I have yet her toilet to make"; and, with a pitying

shrug, Victorine followed Debby to her aunt's room.<p>



<p>



<p>



"Charming! really elegant!" cried that lady, emerging from her towel with a

rubicund visage. "Drop that braid half an inch lower, and pull the worked end

of her handkerchief out of the right-hand pocket, Vic. There! Now, Dora, don't

run about and get rumpled, but sit quietly down and practice repose till I am

ready."<p>



<p>



<p>



Debby obeyed, and sat mute, with the air of child in its Sunday-best on a

week-day, pleased with the novelty, but somewhat oppressed with the

responsibility of such unaccustomed splendor, and utterly unable to connect any

ideas of repose with tight shoes and skirts in a rampant state of starch.<p>



<p>



"Well, you see, I bet on Lady Gay against Cockadoodle, and if you'll believe me

------- Hullo! there's Mrs. Carroll, and deuse take me if she hasn't got a girl

with her! Look, Seguin!"--and Joe Leavenworth, a "man of the world," aged

twenty, paused in his account of an exciting race to make the announcement.<p>



<p>



<p>



Mr. Seguin, his friend and Mentor, as much his senior in worldly wickedness as

in years, tore himself from his breakfast long enough to survey the newcomers,

and then returned to it, saying, briefly,--<p>



<p>



<p>



"The old lady is worth cultivating,--gives good suppers, and thanks you for

eating them. The girl is well got up, but has no style, and blushes like a

milkmaid. Better fight shy of her, Joe."<p>



<p>



<p>



"Do you think so? Well, now I rather fancy that kind of thing. She's new, you

see, and I get on with that sort of girl the best, for the old ones are so

deused knowing that a fellow has no chance of a ------- By the Lord Harry,

she's eating bread and milk!"<p>



<p>



<p>



Young Leavenworth whisked his glass into his eye, and Mr. Seguin put down his

roll to behold the phenomenon. Poor Debby! her first step had been a wrong one.

<p>



<p>



<p>



All great minds have their weak points. Aunt Pen's was her breakfast, and the

peace of her entire day depended upon the success of that meal. Therefore being

down rather late, the worthy lady concentrated her energies upon the

achievement of a copious repast, and, trusting to former lessons, left Debby to

her own resources for a few fatal moments. After the flutter occasioned by

being scooped into her seat by a severe-nosed waiter, Debby had only courage

enough left to refuse tea and coffee and accept milk. That being done, she took

the first familiar viand that appeared, and congratulated herself upon being

able to get her usual breakfast. With returning composure, she looked about her

and began to enjoy the buzz of voices, the clatter of knives and forks, and the

long lines of faces all intent upon the business of the hour; but her peace was

of short duration. Pausing for a fresh relay of toast, Aunt Pen glanced toward

her niece with the comfortable conviction that her appearance was highly

creditable; and her dismay can be imagined, when she beheld that young lady

placidly devouring a great cup of brown-bread and milk before the eyes of the

assembled multitude. The poor lady choked in her coffee, and between her gasps

whispered irefully behind her napkin,--<p>



<p>



<p>



"For Heaven's sake, Dora put away that mess! The Ellenboroughs are directly

opposite, watching everything you do. Eat that omelet, or anything respectable,

unless you want me to die of mortification."<p>



<p>



<p>



Debby dropped her spoon, and, hastily helping herself from the dish her aunt

pushed toward her, consumed the leathery compound with as much grace as she

could assume, though unable to repress a laugh at Aunt Pen's disturbed

countenance. There was a slight lull in the clatter, and the blithe sound

caused several heads to turn toward the quarter whence it came, for it was as

unexpected and pleasant a sound as a bobolink's song in a cage of shrill-voiced

canaries.<p>



<p>



<p>



"She's a jolly little thing and powerful pretty, so deuse take me if I don't

make up to the old lady and find out who the girl is. I've been introduced to

Mrs. Carroll at our house; but I suppose she won't remember me till I remind

her."<p>



<p>



<p>



The "deuse" declining to accept of his repeated offers, (probably because there

was still too much honor and honesty in the boy,) young Leavenworth sought out

Mrs. Carroll on the piazza, as she and Debby were strolling there an hour

later.<p>



<p>



<p>



"Joe Leavenworth, my dear, from one of our first families,--very wealthy,--fine

match,--pray, be civil,--smooth your hair, hold back your shoulders, and put

down your parasol," murmured Aunt Pen, as the gentleman approached with as much

pleasure in his countenance as it was consistent with manly dignity to express

upon meeting two of the inferior race.<p>



<p>



<p>



"My niece, Miss Dora Wilder. This is her first season at the beach, and we must

endeavor to make it pleasant for her, or she will be getting homesick and

running away to mamma," said Aunt Pen, in her society-tone, after she had

returned his greeting, and perpetrated a polite fiction, by declaring that she

remembered him perfectly, for he was the image of his father.<p>



<p>



<p>



Mr. Leavenworth brought the heels of his varnished boots together with a click,

and executed the latest bow imported, then stuck his glass in his eye and

stared till it fell out, (the glass, not the eye,) upon which he fell into step

with them, remarking,--<p>



<p>



<p>



"I shall be most happy to show the lions: they are deused tame ones, so you

needn't be alarmed, Miss Wilder."<p>



<p>



<p>



Debby was good-natured enough to laugh; and, elated with that success, he

proceeded to pour forth his stores of wit and learning in true collegian style,
